{"title_page": "The Artist (film)", "text_new": "{{short description|2011 film directed by Michel Hazanavicius}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name                 = The Artist\n| image                = The Artist Poster.jpg\n| caption              = Theatrical release poster\n| director             = [[Michel Hazanavicius]]\n| producer             = [[Thomas Langmann]]\n| writer               = Michel Hazanavicius\n| starring             = {{Plainlist|\n*[[Jean Dujardin]]\n*[[B\u00e9r\u00e9nice Bejo]]\n}}\n| music                = [[Ludovic Bource]]\n| cinematography       = [[Guillaume Schiffman]]\n| editing              = {{Plainlist|\n*[[Anne-Sophie Bion]]\n*Michel Hazanavicius}}\n| production companies = {{Plainlist|\n*[[La Petite Reine]]\n*ARP S\u00e9lection\n*[[Orange S.A.#Studio 37|Studio 37]]\n*La Classe Am\u00e9ricaine\n*[[France 3 Cinema]]\n*[[uMedia|U Film]]\n*Jouror Productions\n*JD Prod\n}}\n| distributor          = [[Warner Bros.]] {{small|(France)}}\n| released             = {{Film date|df=yes|2011|05|15|[[2011 Cannes Film Festival|Cannes]]|2011|10|12|France}}\n| runtime              = 100 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 100:23--><ref>{{cite web|url=http://bbfc.co.uk/releases/artist-film|title=''The Artist'' (PG)|work=[[British Board of Film Classification]]|date=20 October 2011|accessdate=22 June 2015}}</ref>\n| country              = France\n| budget               = $15 million\n| gross                = $133.4 million<ref name=\"Boxofficemojo\">{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=artist.htm|title=The Artist (2011)|website=[[Box Office Mojo]]|publisher=[[IMDb|IMDb.com, Inc.]]|accessdate=23 June 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n'''''The Artist''''' is a 2011 French<!-- BEFORE EDITING THIS SUBJECT, PLEASE CONSULT THE ARCHIVES AND THE TALK PAGE. THANK YOU.-->{{#tag:ref|There has been some confusion on whether the film is French or American. The official American website states it \"is the first American film by acclaimed French writer/director Michel Hazanavicius\", while the [[Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences|AMPAS]] and mass media describe it as a French film, given that the film was directed and produced by Frenchmen and that the two lead roles are played by French actors.|group=nb}}<ref name=CannesArtist>{{cite web|url=http://www.festival-cannes.com/en/archives/ficheFilm/id/11169584/year/2011.html |title=Festival de Cannes: ''The Artist''|work=[[Cannes Film Festival|Festival de Cannes]]|accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/world_now/2012/02/reporting-from-paris-the-french-woke-up-to-a-historic-moment-in-their-film-history-with-a-record-breaking-slew-of-oscar-f.html'|title=The Artists' five Oscars prompt joyous reaction in France|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=27 February 2012|accessdate=27 February 2012}} {{Dead link|date=April 2014|bot=RjwilmsiBot}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2012/02/27/world/europe/oscars-the-artist/index.html|first=Nick|last=Thompson|title=How a silent, black-and-white French film won big at the Oscars|work=[[CNN]]|date=27 February 2012|accessdate=27 February 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.businessweek.com/news/2012-02-27/oscar-wins-for-the-artist-mark-record-for-a-french-film.html|first=Tara|last=Patel|title=Oscar Wins for \u2018The Artist\u2019 Mark Record for a French Film|work=[[Bloomberg Businessweek]]|date=27 February 2012|accessdate=27 February 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/02/28/arts/28iht-oscarfr28.html|first=Eric|last=Pfanner|title=French Film Industry Celebrates Its Cultural Exception|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=27 February 2012|accessdate=27 February 2012}}</ref> [[comedy-drama]] film{{#tag:ref|Several sources list the film as a \"romantic comedy\" or a \"romantic comedy-drama\". However, there is no romance plot in the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiewire.com/2011/11/director-michel-hazanavicius-inspired-by-life-of-silent-actor-john-gilbert-in-writing-the-artist-115037/ |title=Director Michel Hazanavicius Inspired By Life Of Silent Actor John Gilbert In Writing \u2018The Artist\u2019 |work=IndieWire |date=18 November 2011|accessdate=12 May 2018}}</ref>|group=nb}} in the style of a [[black-and-white]] [[silent film]] or [[part-talkie]].<ref name=ACEFilmEditors>{{cite web|url=http://ace-filmeditors.org/ace-eddie-awards/nominees-recipients/|title=Nominees & Recipients: ACE Film Editors|work=[[American Cinema Editors]]|accessdate=26 February 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110224185421/http://ace-filmeditors.org/ace-eddie-awards/nominees-recipients/|archivedate=24 February 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goldenglobes.org/nominations/|title=Golden Globe nominations|publisher=Goldenglobes.org|accessdate=17 November 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100108115828/http://www.goldenglobes.org/nominations/|archivedate=8 January 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/the_artist|title=The Artist (2011)|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango]]|accessdate=13 November 2017}}</ref><ref>[http://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/movies/sc-mov-1220-the-artist-20111220,0,2703056.column 'The Artist' is artful in the way it wins you over&nbsp;\u2013 3 1/2 stars] {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20120723052713/www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/movies/sc-mov-1220-the-artist-20111220,0,2703056.column |date=23 July 2012 }} ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''</ref> Written, directed, and co-edited by [[Michel Hazanavicius]], and produced by [[Thomas Langmann]], the film stars [[Jean Dujardin]] and [[B\u00e9r\u00e9nice Bejo]].<ref>{{cite book|title=International Film Guide 2012|first=Ian Hayden|last=Smith|year=2012|isbn=978-1908215017|page=117}}</ref> The story takes place in [[Hollywood]], between 1927 and 1932, and focuses on the relationship of an older silent film star and a rising young actress as silent cinema falls out of fashion and is replaced by the \"[[Sound film|talkies]]\".\n\n''The Artist'' received widespread critical acclaim and won many accolades. Dujardin won [[Cannes Film Festival Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]] at the [[2011 Cannes Film Festival]], where the film premiered. The film was nominated for six [[Golden Globe Award|Golden Globes]], the most of any 2011 film, and won three: [[Golden Globe Award for Best Motion Picture - Musical or Comedy|Best Motion Picture&nbsp;\u2013 Musical or Comedy]], [[Golden Globe Award for Best Original Score|Best Original Score]], and [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor - Motion Picture Musical or Comedy|Best Actor&nbsp;\u2013 Motion Picture Musical or Comedy]] for Dujardin. In January 2012, the film was nominated for twelve [[BAFTA]]s, the most of any film from 2011,<ref name=BBCBAFTA>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-16590364|title=Silent movie ''The Artist'' leads Bafta nominations|work=[[BBC News]]|publisher=[[BBC]]|accessdate=17 January 2012|date=17 January 2012}}</ref> and won seven, including [[BAFTA Award for Best Film|Best Film]], [[BAFTA Award for Best Direction|Best Director]], [[BAFTA Award for Best Actor in a Leading Role|Best Actor]] for Dujardin, and [[BAFTA Award for Best Original Screenplay|Best Original Screenplay]] for Hazanavicius.\n\nIt was nominated for ten [[Academy Awards]] and won five,<ref name=BBCOscar>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-16699960|title=Martin Scorsese's ''Hugo'' leads Oscar charge with 11 nods|work=[[BBC News]]|publisher=[[BBC]]|accessdate=24 January 2012|date=24 January 2012}}</ref> including [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]], [[Academy Award for Best Director|Best Director]] for Hazanavicius, and [[Academy Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]] for Dujardin, making him the first French actor ever to win in this category. It was also the first French-produced film to win Best Picture,<ref>{{cite news|title=Oscars 2012: Billy Crystal's back and 'The Artist' could make history|publisher=[[Chicago Tribune]]|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/music/sns-rt-academy-awards-awardsmt1thewrap35726-20120226,0,3195826.story|accessdate=27 February 2012}}</ref> and the first mainly silent film to win since 1927's ''[[Wings (1927 film)|Wings]]'' won at the [[1st Academy Awards]] in 1929. It was also the first film presented in the [[Aspect ratio|4:3 aspect ratio]] to win since 1953's ''[[From Here to Eternity]]''. Additionally, it was the first [[Black-and-white movie|black-and-white film]] to win since 1993's ''[[Schindler's List]]'', though the latter contained limited colour sequences; it was the first 100% black-and-white film to win since 1960's ''[[The Apartment]]''.\n\nIn France it was nominated for ten [[C\u00e9sar Awards]],<ref name=BBCCesar>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-16759408|title=Kate Winslet to receive honorary Cesar award|work=[[BBC News]]|publisher=[[BBC]]|accessdate=28 January 2012|date=27 January 2012}}</ref> winning six, including [[C\u00e9sar Award for Best Film|Best Film]], [[C\u00e9sar Award for Best Director|Best Director]] for Hazanavicius and [[C\u00e9sar Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]] for Bejo. ''The Artist'' has received more awards than any other French film.<ref>{{cite news|last=Leffler|first=Rebecca|title='The Artist' Wins 6 Cesar Awards, Including Best French Film of the Year|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/race/cesar-awards-the-artist-michel-hazanavicius-294893|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media|Prometheus Global Media, LLC]]|accessdate=27 February 2012|date=24 February 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nIn 1927, silent film star George Valentin is posing for pictures outside the [[premiere]] of his latest hit film when a young woman, Peppy Miller, accidentally bumps into him. Valentin reacts with humor to the accident and shows off with Peppy for the cameras. The next day, Peppy finds herself on the front page of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' with the headline \"Who's That Girl?\" Later, Peppy auditions as a dancer and is spotted by Valentin, who insists that she have a part in Kinograph Studios' next production, despite objections from the studio boss, Al Zimmer. While performing a scene in which they dance together, Valentin and Peppy show great chemistry, despite her being merely an extra. With a little guidance from Valentin (he draws a [[beauty spot]] on her, which will eventually be her trademark, after finding her in his dressing room), Peppy slowly rises through the industry, earning more prominent starring roles.\n\nTwo years later, Zimmer announces the end of production of silent films at Kinograph Studios, but Valentin is dismissive, insisting that sound is just a fad. In a dream, Valentin begins hearing sounds from his environment (as does the audience), but cannot speak himself, then wakes up in a sweat. He decides to produce and direct his own silent film, financing it himself. The film opens on the same day as Peppy's new sound film, as well as the [[Wall Street Crash of 1929|1929 Stock Market Crash]]. Valentin's only chance of avoiding bankruptcy is for his film to be a hit. Unfortunately audiences flock to Peppy's film instead, and Valentin is ruined. His wife, Doris, kicks him out, and he moves into an apartment with his valet/chauffeur, Clifton, and his dog. Peppy goes on to become a major Hollywood star.\n\nLater, the bankrupt Valentin is forced to auction off all of his personal effects, and after realizing he has not paid loyal Clifton in over a year, gives him the car and fires him, telling him to get another job. Depressed and drunk, Valentin angrily sets a match to his private collection of his earlier films. As the [[Nitrocellulose#Film|nitrate film]] quickly blazes out of control he is overwhelmed by the smoke and passes out inside the burning house, still clutching a single film canister. However, Valentin's dog attracts the help of a nearby policeman, and after being rescued Valentin is hospitalized for injuries suffered in the fire. Peppy visits the hospital and discovers that the film he rescued is the one with them dancing together. She asks for him to be moved to her house to recuperate. Valentin awakens in a bed at her house, to find that Clifton is now working for Peppy. Valentin seems to remain dismissive of Peppy having taken him in, prompting Clifton to sternly remind Valentin of his changing luck.\n\nPeppy insists to Zimmer that Valentin co-star in her next film, threatening to quit Kinograph if Zimmer does not agree to her terms. After Valentin learns to his dismay that it had been Peppy who had purchased all his auctioned effects, he returns in despair to his burnt-out apartment. Peppy arrives, panicked, and finds that Valentin is about to attempt suicide with a handgun. Peppy tells him she only wanted to help him. They embrace and Valentin tells her it's no use; no one wants to hear him speak. Remembering Valentin's superb dancing ability, Peppy persuades Zimmer to let them make a [[Musical film#The classical sound era|musical]] together.\n\nNow the audience hears sound for the second time, as the film starts rolling for a dance scene with Peppy and Valentin and their tap-dancing can be heard. Once the choreography is complete, the two dancers are heard panting. The director of the musical calls out audibly, \"Cut!\" to which Zimmer adds: \"Perfect. Beautiful. Could you give me just one more?\" Valentin, in his only audible line, replies \"With pleasure,\" revealing a [[French accent]].<ref name=\"themarysue\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.themarysue.com/cinema-scope-a-short-history-of-the-end-of-silent-film/|title=Cinema Scope: A Short History of the End of Silent Film|accessdate=13 March 2013|publisher=[[Dan Abrams#The Mary Sue|The Mary Sue]]}}</ref> The camera then pulls back to the sounds of the film crew as they prepare to shoot another take.\n\n==Cast==\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n*[[Jean Dujardin]] as George Valentin\n*[[B\u00e9r\u00e9nice Bejo]] as Peppy Miller\n*[[Uggie]] as the dog, Jack\n*[[John Goodman]] as Al Zimmer\n*[[James Cromwell]] as Clifton\n*[[Missi Pyle]] as Constance\n*[[Penelope Ann Miller]] as Doris Valentin\n*[[Malcolm McDowell]] as The Butler\n*[[Bitsie Tulloch]] as Norma\n*[[Beth Grant]] as Peppy's maid\n*[[Ed Lauter]] as Peppy's first chauffeur\n*[[Jen Lilley]] as Onlooker\n*[[Nina Siemaszko]] as Admiring woman\n*[[Jewel Shepard]] as Flapper starlet\n*[[Basil Hoffman]] as Auctioneer\n*[[Ben Kurland]] as Casting assistant\n*[[Ken Davitian]] as Pawnbroker\n*[[Bill Fagerbakke]] as Policeman\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Production==\n[[File:\u00c9quipe The Artist Cannes 2011.jpg|thumb|400px|Some of the cast and crew at the [[2011 Cannes Film Festival]]: (left to right), score composer [[Ludovic Bource]], director [[Michel Hazanavicius]], stars [[Missi Pyle]], [[B\u00e9r\u00e9nice Bejo]], and [[Jean Dujardin]], director of photography [[Guillaume Schiffman]] and producer [[Thomas Langmann]].]]\nDirector [[Michel Hazanavicius]] had been fantasizing about making a [[silent film]] for many years, both because many filmmakers he admires emerged in the silent era, and because of the image-driven nature of the form. According to Hazanavicius, his wish to make a silent film was at first not taken seriously, but after the financial success of his spy-film pastiches ''[[OSS 117: Cairo, Nest of Spies]]'' and ''[[OSS 117: Lost in Rio]]'', producers started to express interest. The forming of the film's narrative started with Hazanavicius' desire to work again with actors [[Jean Dujardin]] and [[B\u00e9r\u00e9nice Bejo]], who had both starred in ''OSS 117: Cairo, Nest of Spies''. Hazanavicius chose the form of a [[melodrama]], mostly because he thought many of the films from the silent era that have aged best are of that genre. He did extensive research about 1920s Hollywood, and studied silent films to find the right techniques to make the story comprehensible without having to use too many [[intertitle]]s. The screenplay took four months to write and was principally inspired by the 1928 silent comedy, ''[[Show People]]''.<ref name=presskitmh>{{cite web|url=http://www.festival-cannes.com/assets/Image/Direct/041179.PDF |title=Interview with Michel Hazanavicius |work=English press kit The Artist |publisher=[[Wild Bunch (film company)|Wild Bunch]] |accessdate=10 May 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110914011421/http://www.festival-cannes.com/assets/Image/Direct/041179.PDF |archivedate=14 September 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nyu.edu/alumni.magazine/issue19/pdf/NYU19.pdf|title=The Clothes Make the Man|last=Alfuso|first=Renee|date=Fall 2012|work=NYU Alumni Magazine|access-date=24 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nChief among the influences shaping the screenplay's protagonist was [[Douglas Fairbanks]]. The Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences\u2019 recent book ''Douglas Fairbanks'', by [[Jeffrey Vance]], as well as the Academy's Douglas Fairbanks exhibition and screening events both in Los Angeles and New York City, afforded Hollywood's first swashbuckling hero and the Academy's first president some significant media attention.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.sfgate.com/tgladysz/2012/07/08/film-historian-jeffrey-vance-talks-about-douglas-fairbanks/|title=Film historian Jeffrey Vance talks about Douglas Fairbanks|author=Thomas Gladysz|date=8 July 2012|work=City Brights: Thomas Gladysz|accessdate=2 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://aaspeechesdb.oscars.org/link/084-1/|title=Academy Awards Acceptance Speeches - Search Results - Margaret Herrick Library - Academy of Motion Picture Arts & Sciences|publisher=|accessdate=2 April 2016}}</ref> \n\n[[Principal photography]] on ''The Artist'' began in November 2010,<ref>{{cite journal | author=Erin Carlson | url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/uggie-the-artist-retiring-287271 | title='The Artist' Dog Uggie Retiring Early Due to Mystery Illness (Report) | journal=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] | date=6 February 2014 | accessdate=1 September 2015}}</ref> taking place over the course of thirty-five days,<ref name=BAFTARed>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/iplayer/episode/b01c89nf/The_Orange_British_Academy_Film_Awards_2012_Red_Carpet/ |title=The Orange British Academy Film Awards&nbsp;\u2013 2012 Red Carpet |publisher=BBC News |accessdate=10 February 2012}}</ref> made in the 1.33:1 screen ratio commonly used in the silent film era. Though presented in black-and-white, it was shot in color by [[cinematographer]] [[Guillaume Schiffman]].<ref name=time>{{cite news|first=Gilbert|last=Cruz|title=What Is This Artist Movie That's Winning All the Awards? |url=http://entertainment.time.com/2012/01/19/what-is-this-artist-movie-thats-winning-all-the-awards/ |work=Time Magazine |date=19 January 2012 |accessdate=12 February 2012}}</ref> All the technical details, including lenses, lighting and camera moves, were calibrated to aesthetically match silent films of the period.<ref>Steve Rose, \"Now in full retrovision\", ''The Guardian'' (''The Guide'' supplement), 7 January 2012</ref> To recreate the slightly sped-up look of 1920s silent films, the film was shot at a slightly lower [[frame rate]] of 22 fps as opposed to the standard 24 fps.<ref>{{Cite news | author = Rebecca Keegan | title = Buzz is growing over a silent film | date = 21 November 2011 | url = http://articles.latimes.com/2011/nov/21/entertainment/la-ca-1120-artist-silent-movie-20111121 |work=Los Angeles Times | accessdate=28 January 2012}}</ref> Most of the film is silent, except for two brief scenes with sound as well as the [[Cinematic techniques#Sound|non-diegetic]] soundtrack. Throughout the shoot, Hazanavicius played music from classic Hollywood films while the actors performed.<ref name=presskitmh />\n\nThe film was produced by La Petite Reine and ARP S\u00e9lection for 13.47 million euro, including co-production support from Studio 37 and [[France 3|France 3 Cin\u00e9ma]], and pre-sales investment from [[Canal+]] and Cin\u00e9Cin\u00e9ma.<ref name=outofcomp>{{cite web|last=Lemercier|first=Fabien|date=18 April 2011|url=http://cineuropa.org/newsdetail.aspx?lang=en&documentID=201597|title=Media frenzy over Sarkozy's election ''Conquest''|work=Cineuropa|accessdate=10 May 2011}}</ref> The cast and the crew included both French and American members.<ref name=presskitmh /> All the scenes were shot in [[Los Angeles]], primarily in [[Hollywood]], but also in downtown theaters, restaurants and houses, including the one in which [[Mary Pickford]] lived. Soundstage work was done at [[Ren-Mar Studios|Red Studios]], and the studio lot itself doubled for part of the fictional Kinograph Studios lot, with Red's Lillian Way entrance doubling as the Kinograph entrance in several sequences. The iconic [[Bradbury Building]] in downtown L.A. provided the location for the film's distinctive staircase sequence. The dance sequence that closes the film took seventeen takes, and required Dujardin and Bejo to spend five months studying tap dancing, with Dujardin claiming that \"in the first week it's fun, the fifth week it's a little boring, at the end it's thrilling\".<ref>\"The Artist: The Making of An American Romance\" Featurette, ''The Artist'' DVD</ref>\n\nAmerican [[costume design]]er [[Mark Bridges (costume designer)|Mark Bridges]] created the wardrobe for the film's cast.<ref name=sfgate>{{cite news|first=Hugh|last=Hart|title='Artist' costumer had designs on career as child |url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2012/02/12/PKJC1N1Q6V.DTL |work=San Francisco Chronicle |date=12 February 2011 |accessdate=12 February 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Music==\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = The Artist: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack\n| type       = Soundtrack\n| artist     = [[Ludovic Bource]]\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = 10 October 2011\n| recorded   = 2011\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Soundtrack]]\n| length     = 77:39\n| label      = [[Sony Classical Records]]\n| producer   =\n| chronology = Ludovic Bource\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n{{Album ratings\n|rev1 = [http://www.filmtracks.com/titles/artist.html Filmtracks]\n|rev1score = {{rating|4|5}}\n|rev2 = [http://moviemusicuk.us/2011/11/29/the-artist-ludovic-bource/ Movie Music UK]\n|rev2score = {{rating|4|5}}\n|rev3 = [http://screeninvasion.com/2011/11/soundtrack-review-the-artist/#.UImCRW-HLng Screen Invasion]\n|rev3score = {{rating|5|5}}\n|rev4 = [http://staticmass.net/soundtracks/the-artist-soundtrack-cd-2012-review/ Static Mass Emporium]\n|rev4score = {{rating|5|5}}\n}}\nThe [[Film score|film's music]] was largely composed by [[Ludovic Bource]], but includes works by other composers such as [[Alberto Ginastera]]'s \"Estancia\". The soundtrack was recorded in Belgium by the [[Brussels Philharmonic]] and was conducted by Ernst Van Tiel; the Brussels Jazz Orchestra also cooperated. The recording took place during six days in April 2011 at [[Place Flagey|Flagey]]'s Studio 4 in Brussels.<ref>{{cite web|title=Soundtrack for 'The artist' recorded at Brussels|url=http://www.brusselsphilharmonic.be/en/news/detail/article/soundtrack-voor-the-artist-komt-uit-brussel/|publisher=Brussels Philharmonic|accessdate=30 January 2012|date=3 October 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe film's climactic scene is set to [[Bernard Herrmann]]'s \"Sc\u00e8ne d'amour\" from [[Vertigo (film score)|his score]] to [[Alfred Hitchcock]]'s film ''[[Vertigo (film)|Vertigo]]''. In ''Vertigo'', that composition similarly accompanies an extended scene without dialogue. Only one song (sung, with lyrics) is used in the soundtrack, \"[[Pennies from Heaven (song)|Pennies from Heaven]]\", sung by [[Rose Murphy|Rose \"Chi-Chi\" Murphy]] (uncredited). This song was written in 1936 although the film is set between 1927 and 1932.\n\nThe soundtrack was released on 21 October 2011 through [[Sony Classical Records]].<ref>{{cite web|title=The Artist|url=https://www.amazon.com/Artist-Ludovic-Bource/dp/B005LL4U54|publisher=Amazon.com|accessdate=30 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Track listing===\n{{Track listing\n| extra_column = Performer(s)\n| title1       = The Artist Ouverture\n| length1      = 1:02\n| extra1       = Ernst Van Tiel & the Brussels Philharmonic\n| title2       = 1927: A Russian Affair\n| length2      = 3:36\n| extra2       = Ernst Van Tiel & the Brussels Philharmonic\n| title3       = George Valentin\n| length3      = 5:35\n| extra3       = Ernst Van Tiel & the Brussels Philharmonic\n| title4       = Pretty Peppy\n| length4      = 2:32\n| extra4       = Ernst Van Tiel & the Brussels Philharmonic\n| title5       = At the Kinograph Studios\n| length5      = 1:37\n| extra5       = Ernst Van Tiel & the Brussels Philharmonic\n| title6       = Fantaisie d'amour\n| length6      = 3:09\n| extra6       = Ernst Van Tiel & the Brussels Philharmonic\n| title7       = Waltz for Peppy\n| length7      = 3:22\n| extra7       = Ernst Van Tiel & the Brussels Philharmonic\n| title8       = Estancia Op. 8 Movement 2\" <small>(written by Alberto Ginastera)</small>\n| length8      = 3:40\n| extra8       = Ernst Van Tiel & the Brussels Philharmonic\n| title9       = Imagination\n| length9      = 2:56\n| extra9       = [[Red Nichols]] & His Five Pennies\n| title10      = Silent Rumble\n| length10     = 1:16\n| extra10      = Ernst Van Tiel & the Brussels Philharmonic\n| title11      = 1929\n| length11     = 1:30\n| extra11      = Ernst Van Tiel & the Brussels Philharmonic\n| title12      = In the Stairs\n| length12     = 3:15\n| extra12      = Ernst Van Tiel & the Brussels Philharmonic\n| title13      = Jubilee Stomp\n| length13     = 2:33\n| extra13      = [[Duke Ellington]]\n| title14      = Comme une ros\u00e9e de larmes\n| length14     = 3:24\n| extra14      = Ernst Van Tiel & the Brussels Philharmonic\n| title15      = The Sound of Tears\n| length15     = 4:47\n| extra15      = Ernst Van Tiel & the Brussels Philharmonic\n| title16      = [[Pennies from Heaven (song)|Pennies from Heaven]]\n| length16     = 2:13\n| extra16      = [[Rose Murphy]]\n| title17      = 1931\n| length17     = 4:44\n| extra17      = Ernst Van Tiel & the Brussels Philharmonic\n| title18      = Jungle Bar\n| length18     = 2:07\n| extra18      = Ernst Van Tiel & the Brussels Philharmonic\n| title19      = L'Ombre des flammes\n| length19     = 5:57\n| extra19      = Ernst Van Tiel & the Brussels Philharmonic\n| title20      = Happy Ending...\n| length20     = 5:43\n| extra20      = Ernst Van Tiel & the Brussels Philharmonic\n| title21      = Charming Blackmail\n| length21     = 2:12\n| extra21      = Ernst Van Tiel & the Brussels Philharmonic\n| title22      = Ghosts from the Past\n| length22     = 2:00\n| extra22      = Ernst Van Tiel & the Brussels Philharmonic\n| title23      = My Suicide (Dedicated to 29 March 1967)\n| length23     = 6:24\n| extra23      = Ernst Van Tiel & the Brussels Philharmonic\n| title24      = Peppy and George\n| length24     = 2:05\n| extra24      = Ernst Van Tiel & the Brussels Philharmonic\n}}\n\n===Chart positions===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Chart (2012)\n!Peak<br>position\n|-\n{{albumchart|Flanders|52|artist=Soundtrack / Ludovic Bource|album=The Artist|accessdate=26 October 2013}}\n|-\n{{albumchart|Wallonia|70|artist=Soundtrack / Ludovic Bource|album=The Artist|accessdate=26 October 2013}}\n|-\n{{albumchart|France|37|artist=Soundtrack / Ludovic Bource|album=The Artist|accessdate=26 October 2013}}\n|-\n{{albumchart|Spain|37|artist=Soundtrack / Ludovic Bource|album=The Artist|accessdate=26 October 2013}}\n|-\n|US [[Top Soundtracks]] (''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'')<ref name = \"AllmusicAwards\">[http://www.allmusic.com/album/the-artist-mw0002246650/awards Ludovic Bource - The Artist Awards]. [[Allmusic]]. Retrieved 26 October 2013.</ref>\n|align=center|19\n|}\n\n===Certifications===\n{{Certification Table Top}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=France|type=album|artist=Ludovic Bource|title=The Artist|award=Platinum|relyear=2012|certyear=2012|certref=<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.actu.snepmusique.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/10/DISQUES-DOR-2012_site.pdf|title=ANNEE 2012 - CERTIFICATIONS AU 31/10/2012|publisher=[[Syndicat National de l'\u00c9dition Phonographique]]|year=2012|access-date=3 December 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121110045848/http://www.actu.snepmusique.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/10/DISQUES-DOR-2012_site.pdf|archivedate=10 November 2012}}</ref>}}\n{{Certification Table Bottom}}\n\n==Release==\n{{multiple image\n| align = right\n| image1 = Jean Dujardin Cannes 2011.jpg\n| width1 = 121\n| alt1 = \n| caption1 = \n| image2 = Berenice Bejo Cannes 2011 cropped.jpg\n| width2 = 110\n| alt2 = \n| caption2 = \n| footer = [[Jean Dujardin]] and [[B\u00e9r\u00e9nice Bejo]] at the [[2011 Cannes Film Festival]]\n}}\nThe film premiered on 15 May 2011 in competition at the [[2011 Cannes Film Festival]].<ref name=\"Cannes\">{{cite web|url=http://www.festival-cannes.fr/assets/File/Web/HORAIRES%202011/Horaire%20internet.pdf|title=Horaires 2011|language=French|work=festival-cannes.com|publisher=[[Cannes Film Festival]]|accessdate=10 May 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120123034309/http://www.festival-cannes.fr/assets/File/Web/HORAIRES%202011/Horaire%20internet.pdf|archive-date=23 January 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> It was initially announced as an out of competition entry, but was moved to the competition a week before the festival opened.<ref>{{cite web|last=Mitchell|first=Wendy|date=4 May 2011|url=http://www.screendaily.com/festivals/cannes/hazanavicius-the-artist-moves-into-competition-in-cannes/5026923.article|title=Hazanavicius' The Artist moves into Competition in Cannes|work=[[Screen International|Screen Daily]]|accessdate=10 May 2011}}</ref> The French regular release was on 12 October 2011 through [[Warner Bros.|Warner Bros. France]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allocine.fr/film/fichefilm_gen_cfilm=183070.html|title=The Artist|language=French|work=[[AlloCin\u00e9]]|publisher=[[Tiger Management|Tiger Global]]|accessdate=10 May 2011}}</ref> [[The Weinstein Company]] bought the distribution rights for the United States and Australia and [[Entertainment Film Distributors]] bought the UK distribution.<ref>{{cite web|last=Tartaglione|first=16 May 2011|url=http://www.screendaily.com/news/distribution/wild-bunch-weinsteins-confirm-multi-territory-deal-on-the-artist/5027596.article|title=Wild Bunch, Weinsteins confirm multi-territory deal on The Artist|work=[[Screen International|Screen Daily]]|accessdate=22 May 2011}}</ref> The film was initially given a [[limited release]] in the United States on 23 November 2011.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.cinemablend.com/new/Artist-Star-Jean-Dujardin-How-Gene-Kelly-Inspired-His-Work-28076.html | work=CinemaBlend.com | title=The Artist Star Jean Dujardin On How Gene Kelly Inspired His Work | date=28 November 2011 | accessdate=12 May 2012 | first1=Katey | last1=Rich}}</ref>\n\nFollowing its wins at the [[69th Golden Globe Awards]], it was announced Warner Bros. would re-release the film in France in 362 theaters on 25 January 2012.<ref>{{cite web|title=\" The Artist \" ressort en salles en France|url=http://archives.lesoir.be/-the-artist-ressort-en-salles-en-france_t-20120116-01RKP5.html|work=[[Le Soir]]|accessdate=27 February 2012|language=French|date=16 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Keslassy|first=Elsa|title=France's second look at 'Artist'|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1118050616|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|accessdate=27 February 2012|date=22 February 2012}}</ref> It was also re-released in Belgium on 22 February 2012.<ref>{{cite web|title=\"The Artist\" remporte 7 Bafta Awards dont meilleur film, meilleur r\u00e9alisateur et meillleur acteur.|url=http://www.cineart.be/fr/news/the-artist-remporte-7-bafta-awards-dont-meilleur-film-meilleur-realisateur-et-meilleur-acteur.aspx|publisher=cin\u00e9art.be|accessdate=27 February 2012|language=French|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130910140717/http://www.cineart.be/fr/news/the-artist-remporte-7-bafta-awards-dont-meilleur-film-meilleur-realisateur-et-meilleur-acteur.aspx|archivedate=10 September 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Box office===\n''The Artist'' grossed $44,671,682 in North America, along with $88,761,174 in other territories for a worldwide total of $133,432,856.<ref name=\"Boxofficemojo\" /> After its success at the Academy Awards, the film saw a moderate boost the following week on the box office in North America. It appeared on the week's top 10 chart and got an increase of 34% while expanding its release from 966 theaters to 1,756.<ref>{{cite news|last=McClintock|first=Pamela|title='The Artist' Enjoys Box Office Bump After Oscar Wins|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/artist-box-office-oscars-michel-Hazanavicius-Jean-Dujardin-296749|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media|Prometheus Global Media, LLC]]|accessdate=4 May 2012|date=4 March 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\n<!-- WHEN UPDATING REVIEW AGGREGATE SCORES, PLEASE MAKE SURE YOU UPDATE THE NUMBER OF REVIEWS AND THE ACCESS DATE IN THE CITATION! -->\nOn review aggregator [[Rotten Tomatoes]] the film has an approval rating of 95% based on 310 reviews, with an [[weighted arithmetic mean|average rating]] of 8.83/10. The website's critical consensus states, \"A crowd-pleasing tribute to the magic of silent cinema, ''The Artist'' is a clever, joyous film with delightful performances and visual style to spare.\"<ref name=\"RottenTomatoes\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/the_artist/|title=''The Artist'' (2011)|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango]]|accessdate=13 July 2019}}</ref> At [[Metacritic]], which assigns a weighted mean rating to reviews, the film received an average score of 89 out of 100, based on 41 critics, indicating \"universal acclaim\".<ref name=\"Metacritic\">{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/the-artist|title=''The Artist'' Reviews|work=[[Metacritic]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive|CBS Interactive Inc.]]|accessdate=27 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nMark Adams of ''[[Screen International|Screen Daily]]'' called the film \"a real pleasure\"; \"propelled elegantly forward by delightful performances from Jean Dujardin and B\u00e9r\u00e9nice Bejo it is the most unlikely of feel-good movies.\" He added however: \"The film does feel a little sluggish towards the end of the first third as the music is a little repetitive and the intertitles are infrequent, but Hazanavicius manages to give the film a real sense of charm and warmth, and film fans will be competing to spot visual and musical references.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Adams|first=Mark|date=15 May 2011|url=http://www.screendaily.com/reviews/latest-reviews/the-artist/5027562.article|title=The Artist|work=[[Screen International|Screen Daily]]|accessdate=22 May 2011}}</ref> Peter Bradshaw of ''[[The Guardian]]'' described how the film \"had me on my feet cheering throughout the final credits\" and stated \"I can't wait to see it again\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Bradshaw|first=Peter|authorlink=Peter Bradshaw|title=Cannes 2011: The Artist/Michael/Footnote&nbsp;\u2013 review|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2011/may/16/cannes-2011-the-artist-michael-footnote-review|work=[[The Guardian]]|publisher=[[Guardian Media Group|Guardian News and Media Limited]]|location=UK|accessdate=27 October 2011|date=16 May 2011}}</ref>\n\nGeoffrey McNab at ''[[The Independent]]'' called the film \"both a surefire crowdpleaser and a magnificent piece of film-making\" in his 5 star review from the [[Cannes Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite news|last=McNab|first=Geoffrey|title=The Artist, Cannes Film Festival|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/reviews/the-artist-cannes-film-festival-2285354.html|work=[[The Independent]]|publisher=Independent Digital News & Media Limited|location=UK|accessdate=27 October 2011|date=18 May 2011}}</ref> Rick Groen of ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'' assessed ''The Artist'' highly, noting the film \"uses old technology to dazzling effect to illustrate the insistent conquest of a new technology.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/arts/movies/the-artist-mostly-mute-it-speaks-volumes-about-silent-film/article2264777/|title=The Artist: Mostly mute, it speaks volumes about silent film|work=[[The Globe and Mail]]|publisher=The Globe and Mail Limited|first=Rick|last=Groen|date=9 December 2011|accessdate=13 January 2012|location=Toronto}}</ref> Sukanya Verma for [[Rediff.com]] feels ''The Artist'' is an extremely well-researched film and is an instant classic.<ref name=\"Review : The Artist \">{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/review/review-the-artist-is-an-instant-classic/20120224.htm| title=Review: The Artist is an instant classic | author=Sukanya Verma | publisher=Rediff.com | accessdate=24 February 2012}}</ref> David Thomson of ''[[The New Republic]]'' called ''The Artist'' an \"accomplished and witty entertainment\" and went on to write, \"Whether Hazanavicius can do more things as elegant and touching, without the gimmick of silence, remains to be seen (and heard). Meanwhile, he is to be congratulated on the grounds of pleasure alone. He may be due for much more in the way of rewards.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.tnr.com/article/film/99237/artist-cannes-hazanavicius-dujardin |title=Why \u2018The Artist\u2019 Just Might Win the Oscars |author=David Thomson | publisher=The New Republic | date= 5 January 2012}}</ref> ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' [[film criticism|film critic]] [[Roger Ebert]] gave the film four out of four stars, praising the performances, and calling the film \"one of the most entertaining films in many a moon, a film that charms because of its story, its performances and because of the sly way it plays with being silent and black and white.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Ebert|first=Roger|authorlink=Roger Ebert|url=http://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/the-artist-2011|title=The Artist review|website=[[RogerEbert.com]]|publisher=Ebert Digital LLC|date=25 July 2013}}</ref>\n\nWriting for ''[[Slant Magazine]]'', Jaime N. Christley gave the film one-and-a-half out of four stars, explaining Michel Hazanavicius ignores \"everything that's fascinating and memorable about the era, focusing instead on a patchwork of general knowledge, so eroded of inconvenient facts that it doesn't even qualify as a ''roman \u00e0 clef''.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Film Review \u2013 The Artist|url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/film/review/the-artist/5846|work=[[Slant Magazine]]|accessdate=27 February 2012|author=Jaime N. Christley|date=16 October 2011}}</ref> ''[[America (magazine)|America]]'' argued that while Jean Dujardin carried the film, Bejo's performance was disappointing.<ref name=\"america\">{{cite news |title=The French Connection |first=Victor |last=Stepien |url=http://www.americamagazine.org/content/culture.cfm?cultureID=258 |newspaper=[[America (Jesuit magazine)|America]] |date=12 March 2012 |accessdate=6 March 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Kim Novak controversy===\nOn 9 January 2012, actress [[Kim Novak]] stated that \"rape\" had been committed in the film's licensed use of a portion of [[Bernard Herrmann]]'s score from [[Alfred Hitchcock]]'s 1958 film ''[[Vertigo (film)|Vertigo]]'' (in which Novak starred). The final portion of ''The Artist'' is accompanied not by original music, but by a 1992 recording of the Herrmann composition ''Scene d'Amour'', conducted by [[Elmer Bernstein]]. In the article published, by ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'', she stated that \"I feel as if my body&nbsp;\u2014 or at least my body of work&nbsp;\u2014 has been violated by the movie.\"<ref name=\"Vertigo\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-16482624|title=Artist director responds to Kim Novak Vertigo claim|work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |accessdate=10 January 2012 |date=10 January 2012}}</ref> \"This film should've been able to stand on its own without depending on Bernard Herrmann's score from Alfred Hitchcock's 'Vertigo' to provide more drama\" and that \"It is morally wrong for the artistry of our industry to use and abuse famous pieces of work to gain attention and applause for other than what they were intended\", ending her comments with \"Shame on them!\"<ref name=\"CNN\">{{cite news|title='The Artist' director defends use of Hitchcock score|url=http://marquee.blogs.cnn.com/2012/01/10/the-artist-director-defends-use-of-hitchcock-score/|work=The Marquee Blog|publisher=CNN|accessdate=12 January 2012|date=10 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn response, director Hazanavicius released a statement:<blockquote>''The Artist'' was made as a love letter to cinema, and grew out of my (and all of my cast and crew\u2019s) admiration and respect for movies throughout history. It was inspired by the work of Hitchcock, [[Fritz Lang|Lang]], [[John Ford|Ford]], [[Ernst Lubitsch|Lubitsch]], [[F. W. Murnau|Murnau]] and [[Billy Wilder|Wilder]]. I love Bernard Herrmann and his music has been used in many different films and I\u2019m very pleased to have it in mine. I respect Kim Novak greatly and I\u2019m sorry to hear she disagrees.<ref>{{cite news|title='The Artist' Director Responds to Kim Novak Slam Over 'Vertigo' Music|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/race/artist-kim-novak-michel-hazanavicius-279757|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=12 January 2012|date=9 January 2012}}</ref></blockquote> Hazanavicius also told [[CNN]] \"I used music from another movie, but it\u2019s not illegal. We paid for that, we asked for that and we had the permission to do it. For me there is no real controversy.... I feel sorry for her, but there\u2019s a lot of movies with music from other movies, directors do that all the time and I\u2019m not sure it\u2019s a big deal.\"<ref name=\"CNN\" />\n\nIn May 2011, when the film was first shown at the Cannes Festival, [[Todd McCarthy]] from ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' mentioned the use of Herrmann's music, \"Hazanavicius and Bource daringly choose to explicitly employ Bernard Herrmann\u2019s love theme from ''Vertigo'', which is dramatically effective in its own right but is so well known that it yanks you out of one film and places you in the mind-set of another. Surely some sort of reworked equivalent would have been a better idea.\"<ref name=McCarthy>{{cite news|last=McCarthy|first=Todd|title=The Artist: Cannes Review|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/artist-cannes-review-188493|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media|Prometheus Global Media, LLC]]|accessdate=12 January 2012|date=15 May 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Top ten lists===\nThe film has appeared on the following critics' top ten lists for the best films of 2011:\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 100%;\"\n|-\n! Critic\n! Publication\n! Rank\n|- 1st.\n| [[Richard Corliss]] || ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]''||1st<ref>{{cite news|last=Corliss|first=Richard|title=The Top 10 Everything of 2011&nbsp;\u2013 The Artist|url=http://www.time.com/time/specials/packages/article/0,28804,2101344_2101362_2101351,00.html|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|accessdate=17 December 2011|date=7 December 2011}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Peter Bradshaw]] || ''[[The Guardian]]''||1st<ref name=\"metacritic top ten\">{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/feature/movie-critic-best-of-2011-top-ten-lists |title=2011 Film Critic Top Ten Lists [Updated Dec. 22] |first=Jason |last=Dietz |work=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |date=8 December 2011 |accessdate=23 December 2011}}</ref>\n|-\n| Robbie Collin || ''[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]''||1st<ref name=\"metacritic top ten\" />\n|-\n| [[Richard Roeper]] || ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''||2nd<ref>{{cite web |url=http://awardcontenders.com/top-10-lists-from-richard-roeper-michael-phillips-j-hoberman-and-todd-mccarthy/ |title=Top 10 Lists from Richard Roeper, Michael Phillips, J. Hoberman, and Todd McCarthy |work=Chicago Tribune |date=22 December 2011 |accessdate=19 April 2011}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Peter Travers]] || ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' ||2nd<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/lists/10-best-movies-of-2011-20111207/the-artist-19691231|title=10 Best Movies of 2011: The Artist |first=Peter |last=Travers |work=Rolling Stone|date=8 December 2011 |accessdate=17 December 2011}}</ref>\n|-\n| Elizabeth Weitzman||''[[New York Daily News]]''||2nd<ref name=\"metacritic top ten\"/>\n|-\n| [[Lisa Schwarzbaum]] || ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' || 3rd<ref name=\"metacritic top ten\"/>\n|-\n| [[Mark Kermode]] || [[BBC Radio 5 Live]] || 4th<ref>{{cite web|title=\nEleven from Eleven |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/markkermode/2012/01/eleven_from_eleven.html |work=BBC |accessdate=11 January 2012|date=6 January 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n| Richard T. Jameson || [[MSN|MSN Movies]] || 4th<ref name=\"metacritic top ten\"/>\n|-\n| Sean Axmaker || MSN Movies || 5th<ref name=\"metacritic top ten\"/>\n|-\n| ''Empire''{{'}}s writers and contributors || ''[[Empire Magazine]]''||5th<ref name=\"metacritic top ten\" />\n|-\n| [[James Berardinelli]] || ''Reelviews'' || 5th<ref>{{cite web|title=Rewinding 2011: The Top 10 |url=http://www.reelviews.net/reelthoughts.php?identifier=683 |work=Reelviews |accessdate=26 February 2012|date=31 December 2011}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''S&S'' international poll of critics || ''[[Sight & Sound]]'' ||5th<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bfi.org.uk/sightandsound/feature/49804|title=2011: The year in review|work=Sight & Sound|date=17 December 2011|accessdate=17 December 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120104140414/http://www.bfi.org.uk/sightandsound/feature/49804|archivedate=4 January 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n| Austin Film Critics Association || [[Austin Film Critics Association]] ||6th<ref>{{cite web|url=http://austinfilmcritics.org/2011.html|title=2011 Awards|work=Austin Film Critics|date=17 December 2011|accessdate=17 December 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120108081300/http://austinfilmcritics.org/2011.html|archivedate=8 January 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Roger Ebert]] || ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' || 10th<ref name=\"metacritic top ten\"/>\n|-\n| ''Time Out''{{'}}s film team || ''[[Time Out London]]'' || 10th<ref name=\"metacritic top ten\"/>\n|}\n\n===Accolades===\n{{main|List of accolades received by The Artist (film)}}\nAt the [[65th British Academy Film Awards]], the film won seven awards, including Best Film, Best Actor for Dujardin, Best Original Screenplay for Hazanavicius, Cinematography for Schiffman, Costume Design for Bridges and Original Score for [[Ludovic Bource]].<ref name=\"Orange BAFTA Film Award Winners\">{{cite web |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/movies/news/a364820/orange-bafta-film-awards-2012-winners-list-in-full.html |title=Orange BAFTA Film Awards 2012 winners list&nbsp;\u2014 in full |publisher=Digital Bits |accessdate=16 February 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"BAFTA 2012 Winners\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2012/feb/12/baftas-2012-winners-full-list?intcmp=239 |title=BAFTA 2012 the winners&nbsp;\u2014 the full list |work=The Guardian |location=UK |date=12 February 2012 |accessdate=16 February 2012}}</ref> At the [[69th Golden Globe Awards]], the film was nominated for six [[Golden Globes]] to win three of them; [[Golden Globe Award for Best Motion Picture - Musical or Comedy|Best Motion Picture&nbsp;\u2013 Musical or Comedy]], [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor - Motion Picture Musical or Comedy|Best Actor&nbsp;\u2013 Motion Picture Musical or Comedy]] for Dujardin and [[Golden Globe Award for Best Musical Score|Best Musical Score]] for Bource.<ref name=\"Golden Globes 2012 Winners\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2012/jan/16/golden-globes-golden-globes-2012 |title=Golden Globes 2012 the winners&nbsp;\u2014 the full list |work=The Guardian |location=UK |date=16 January 2012 |accessdate=17 February 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Golden Globes 2012\">{{cite news |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/golden-globes-2012-winners-list-282032 |title=Golden Globes 2012: The Full List |work=The Hollywood Reporter |date=15 January 2012 |accessdate=17 February 2012}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[84th Academy Awards]], ''The Artist'' received ten nominations, winning five awards, including [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]], [[Academy Award for Best Director|Best Director]] for Hazanavicius, [[Academy Award for Best Actor|Best Actor in a Leading Role]] for [[Jean Dujardin]], [[Academy Award for Best Costume Design|Best Costume Design]], and [[Academy Award for Best Original Score|Best Original Score]].<ref name=\"Oscar winners 2012\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2012/feb/27/oscars-2012-full-list-winners |title=Oscar 2012 winners&nbsp;\u2013 The full list |work=The Guardian |location=UK |date=27 February 2012 |accessdate=28 February 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Academy Awards 2012 winners\">{{cite web |url=http://www.oscars.org/awards/academyawards/84/nominees.html |title=Nominees and Winners for the 84th Academy Awards |publisher=Academy Awards of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences (Oscars) |accessdate=21 February 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-17178811\n|title=France hails The Artist's Oscars triumph |date=27 February 2012 |work=BBC News |accessdate=27 February 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Home media===\n''The Artist'' was released on [[DVD region code|region 1]] [[DVD]] and [[Blu-ray Disc|Blu-ray]] on 26 June 2012.<ref name=Amazon>{{cite web|title=Amazon.com|url=https://www.amazon.com/The-Artist-UltraViolet-Digital-Copy/dp/B00782O7IY/ref=sr_1_1?ie=UTF8&qid=1337129571&sr=8-1|work=Amazon|date=15 May 2012}}</ref> It was released in the UK by [[Entertainment Film Distributors|Entertainment in Video]] on 28 May 2012.<ref>{{cite web|author1=Webmaster|title=The Artist Detailed|url=http://www.blu-ray.com/news/?id=8486|website=Blu-ray.com|publisher=Blu-ray.com|accessdate=12 November 2017|date=4 April 2012}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of black-and-white films produced since 1970]]\n*[[List of films featuring fictional films]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|1|group=nb}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|The Artist (film)}}\n*[http://www.orange-studio.fr/film/264/the-artist.html Orange Studio (Studio 37) official site] {{in lang|fr}}\n*{{IMDb title|1655442}}\n*{{Allmovie title|538544}}\n*{{Mojo title|artist}}\n*{{Metacritic film|the-artist}}\n*{{Rotten Tomatoes|the_artist}}\n\n{{Michel Hazanavicius}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title = [[List of accolades received by The Artist (film)|Awards for ''The Artist'']]\n|list =\n{{AcademyAwardBestPicture 2001\u20132020}}\n{{AACTA International Award for Best Film}}\n{{BAFTA Best Film 2001\u20132020}}\n{{Broadcast Film Critics Association Award for Best Film}}\n{{C\u00e9sar Award for Best Film}}\n{{GoldenGlobeBestMotionPictureMusicalComedy 2001\u20132020}}\n{{Goya Award for Best European Film}}\n{{Independent Spirit Award for Best Film}}\n{{London Film Critics Circle Award for Film of the Year}}\n{{Lumi\u00e8res Award for Best Film}}\n{{New York Film Critics Circle Award for Best Film}}\n{{Producers Guild of America Award for Best Theatrical Motion Picture}}\n{{Vancouver Film Critics Circle Award for Best Film}}\n}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Artist}}\n[[Category:2011 films]]\n[[Category:French films]]\n[[Category:2010s romantic comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:French romantic comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:French silent feature films]]\n[[Category:French black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Michel Hazanavicius]]\n[[Category:Films about actors]]\n[[Category:Films about Hollywood]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1927]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1928]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1929]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1930]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1931]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1932]]\n[[Category:Films set in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Best Picture Academy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Best Film BAFTA Award winners]]\n[[Category:Best Film Lumi\u00e8res Award winners]]\n[[Category:Best Film C\u00e9sar Award winners]]\n[[Category:Best Musical or Comedy Picture Golden Globe winners]]\n[[Category:Independent Spirit Award for Best Film winners]]\n[[Category:Films whose director won the Best Director C\u00e9sar Award]]\n[[Category:Films featuring a Best Actor Academy Award-winning performance]]\n[[Category:Films featuring a Best Actress C\u00e9sar Award-winning performance]]\n[[Category:Films featuring a Best Musical or Comedy Actor Golden Globe winning performance]]\n[[Category:Films featuring a Best Actress Lumi\u00e8res Award-winning performance]]\n[[Category:Films whose director won the Best Directing Academy Award]]\n[[Category:Films that won the Best Costume Design Academy Award]]\n[[Category:Films that won the Best Original Score Academy Award]]\n[[Category:Films set in studio lots]]\n[[Category:Films whose director won the Best Direction BAFTA Award]]\n[[Category:Films whose writer won the Best Original Screenplay BAFTA Award]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Thomas Langmann]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2011 film directed by Michel Hazanavicius}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name                 = The Artist\n| image                = The Artist Poster.jpg\n| caption              = Theatrical release poster\n| director             = [[Michel Hazanavicius]]\n| producer             = [[Thomas Langmann]]\n| writer               = Michel Hazanavicius\n| starring             = {{Plainlist|\n*[[Jean Dujardin]]\n*[[B\u00e9r\u00e9nice Bejo]]\n}}\n| music                = [[Ludovic Bource]]\n| cinematography       = [[Guillaume Schiffman]]\n| editing              = {{Plainlist|\n*[[Anne-Sophie Bion]]\n*Michel Hazanavicius}}\n| production companies = {{Plainlist|\n*[[La Petite Reine]]\n*ARP S\u00e9lection\n*[[Orange S.A.#Studio 37|Studio 37]]\n*La Classe Am\u00e9ricaine\n*[[France 3 Cinema]]\n*[[uMedia|U Film]]\n*Jouror Productions\n*JD Prod\n}}\n| distributor          = [[Warner Bros.]] {{small|(France)}}\n| released             = {{Film date|df=yes|2011|05|15|[[2011 Cannes Film Festival|Cannes]]|2011|10|12|France}}\n| runtime              = 100 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 100:23--><ref>{{cite web|url=http://bbfc.co.uk/releases/artist-film|title=''The Artist'' (PG)|work=[[British Board of Film Classification]]|date=20 October 2011|accessdate=22 June 2015}}</ref>\n| country              = France\n| budget               = $15 million\n| gross                = $133.4 million<ref name=\"Boxofficemojo\">{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=artist.htm|title=The Artist (2011)|website=[[Box Office Mojo]]|publisher=[[IMDb|IMDb.com, Inc.]]|accessdate=23 June 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n'''''The Artist''''' is a 2011 French<!-- BEFORE EDITING THIS SUBJECT, PLEASE CONSULT THE ARCHIVES AND THE TALK PAGE. THANK YOU.-->{{#tag:ref|There has been some confusion on whether the film is French or American. The official American website states it \"is the first American film by acclaimed French writer/director Michel Hazanavicius\", while the [[Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences|AMPAS]] and mass media describe it as a French film, given that the film was directed and produced by Frenchmen and that the two lead roles are played by French actors.|group=nb}}<ref name=CannesArtist>{{cite web|url=http://www.festival-cannes.com/en/archives/ficheFilm/id/11169584/year/2011.html |title=Festival de Cannes: ''The Artist''|work=[[Cannes Film Festival|Festival de Cannes]]|accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/world_now/2012/02/reporting-from-paris-the-french-woke-up-to-a-historic-moment-in-their-film-history-with-a-record-breaking-slew-of-oscar-f.html'|title=The Artists' five Oscars prompt joyous reaction in France|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=27 February 2012|accessdate=27 February 2012}} {{Dead link|date=April 2014|bot=RjwilmsiBot}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2012/02/27/world/europe/oscars-the-artist/index.html|first=Nick|last=Thompson|title=How a silent, black-and-white French film won big at the Oscars|work=[[CNN]]|date=27 February 2012|accessdate=27 February 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.businessweek.com/news/2012-02-27/oscar-wins-for-the-artist-mark-record-for-a-french-film.html|first=Tara|last=Patel|title=Oscar Wins for \u2018The Artist\u2019 Mark Record for a French Film|work=[[Bloomberg Businessweek]]|date=27 February 2012|accessdate=27 February 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/02/28/arts/28iht-oscarfr28.html|first=Eric|last=Pfanner|title=French Film Industry Celebrates Its Cultural Exception|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=27 February 2012|accessdate=27 February 2012}}</ref> [[comedy-drama]] film{{#tag:ref|Several sources list the film as a \"romantic comedy\" or a \"romantic comedy-drama\". However, there is no romance plot in the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiewire.com/2011/11/director-michel-hazanavicius-inspired-by-life-of-silent-actor-john-gilbert-in-writing-the-artist-115037/ |title=Director Michel Hazanavicius Inspired By Life Of Silent Actor John Gilbert In Writing \u2018The Artist\u2019 |work=IndieWire |date=18 November 2011|accessdate=12 May 2018}}</ref>|group=nb}} in the style of a [[black-and-white]] [[silent film]] or [[part-talkie]].<ref name=ACEFilmEditors>{{cite web|url=http://ace-filmeditors.org/ace-eddie-awards/nominees-recipients/|title=Nominees & Recipients: ACE Film Editors|work=[[American Cinema Editors]]|accessdate=26 February 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110224185421/http://ace-filmeditors.org/ace-eddie-awards/nominees-recipients/|archivedate=24 February 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goldenglobes.org/nominations/|title=Golden Globe nominations|publisher=Goldenglobes.org|accessdate=17 November 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100108115828/http://www.goldenglobes.org/nominations/|archivedate=8 January 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/the_artist|title=The Artist (2011)|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango]]|accessdate=13 November 2017}}</ref><ref>[http://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/movies/sc-mov-1220-the-artist-20111220,0,2703056.column 'The Artist' is artful in the way it wins you over&nbsp;\u2013 3 1/2 stars] {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20120723052713/www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/movies/sc-mov-1220-the-artist-20111220,0,2703056.column |date=23 July 2012 }} ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''</ref> Written, directed, and co-edited by [[Michel Hazanavicius]], and produced by [[Thomas Langmann]], the film stars [[Jean Dujardin]] and [[B\u00e9r\u00e9nice Bejo]].<ref>{{cite book|title=International Film Guide 2012|first=Ian Hayden|last=Smith|year=2012|isbn=978-1908215017|page=117}}</ref> The story takes place in [[Hollywood]], between 1927 and 1932, and focuses on the relationship of an older silent film star and a rising young actress as silent cinema falls out of fashion and is replaced by the \"[[Sound film|talkies]]\".\n\n''The Artist'' received widespread critical acclaim and won many accolades. Dujardin won [[Cannes Film Festival Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]] at the [[2011 Cannes Film Festival]], where the film premiered. The film was nominated for six [[Golden Globe Award|Golden Globes]], the most of any 2011 film, and won three: [[Golden Globe Award for Best Motion Picture - Musical or Comedy|Best Motion Picture&nbsp;\u2013 Musical or Comedy]], [[Golden Globe Award for Best Original Score|Best Original Score]], and [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor - Motion Picture Musical or Comedy|Best Actor&nbsp;\u2013 Motion Picture Musical or Comedy]] for Dujardin. In January 2012, the film was nominated for twelve [[BAFTA]]s, the most of any film from 2011,<ref name=BBCBAFTA>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-16590364|title=Silent movie ''The Artist'' leads Bafta nominations|work=[[BBC News]]|publisher=[[BBC]]|accessdate=17 January 2012|date=17 January 2012}}</ref> and won seven, including [[BAFTA Award for Best Film|Best Film]], [[BAFTA Award for Best Direction|Best Director]], [[BAFTA Award for Best Actor in a Leading Role|Best Actor]] for Dujardin, and [[BAFTA Award for Best Original Screenplay|Best Original Screenplay]] for Hazanavicius.\n\nIt was nominated for ten [[Academy Awards]] and won five,<ref name=BBCOscar>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-16699960|title=Martin Scorsese's ''Hugo'' leads Oscar charge with 11 nods|work=[[BBC News]]|publisher=[[BBC]]|accessdate=24 January 2012|date=24 January 2012}}</ref> including [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]], [[Academy Award for Best Director|Best Director]] for Hazanavicius, and [[Academy Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]] for Dujardin, making him the first French actor ever to win in this category. It was also the first French-produced film to win Best Picture,<ref>{{cite news|title=Oscars 2012: Billy Crystal's back and 'The Artist' could make history|publisher=[[Chicago Tribune]]|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/music/sns-rt-academy-awards-awardsmt1thewrap35726-20120226,0,3195826.story|accessdate=27 February 2012}}</ref> and the first mainly silent film to win since 1927's ''[[Wings (1927 film)|Wings]]'' won at the [[1st Academy Awards]] in 1929. It was also the first film presented in the [[Aspect ratio|4:3 aspect ratio]] to win since 1953's ''[[From Here to Eternity]]''. Additionally, it was the first [[Black-and-white movie|black-and-white film]] to win since 1993's ''[[Schindler's List]]'', though the latter contained limited colour sequences; it was the first 100% black-and-white film to win since 1960's ''[[The Apartment]]''.\n\nIn France it was nominated for ten [[C\u00e9sar Awards]],<ref name=BBCCesar>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-16759408|title=Kate Winslet to receive honorary Cesar award|work=[[BBC News]]|publisher=[[BBC]]|accessdate=28 January 2012|date=27 January 2012}}</ref> winning six, including [[C\u00e9sar Award for Best Film|Best Film]], [[C\u00e9sar Award for Best Director|Best Director]] for Hazanavicius and [[C\u00e9sar Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]] for Bejo. ''The Artist'' has received more awards than any other French film.<ref>{{cite news|last=Leffler|first=Rebecca|title='The Artist' Wins 6 Cesar Awards, Including Best French Film of the Year|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/race/cesar-awards-the-artist-michel-hazanavicius-294893|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media|Prometheus Global Media, LLC]]|accessdate=27 February 2012|date=24 February 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nIn 1927, silent film star George Valentin is posing for pictures outside the [[premiere]] of his latest hit film when a young woman, Peppy Miller, accidentally bumps into him. Valentin reacts with humor to the accident and shows off with Peppy for the cameras. The next day, Peppy finds herself on the front page of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' with the headline \"Who's That Girl?\" Later, Peppy auditions as a dancer and is spotted by Valentin, who insists that she have a part in Kinograph Studios' next production, despite objections from the studio boss, Al Zimmer. While performing a scene in which they dance together, Valentin and Peppy show great chemistry, despite her being merely an extra. With a little guidance from Valentin (he draws a [[beauty spot]] on her, which will eventually be her trademark, after finding her in his dressing room), Peppy slowly rises through the industry, earning more prominent starring roles.\n\nTwo years later, Zimmer announces the end of production of silent films at Kinograph Studios, but Valentin is dismissive, insisting that sound is just a fad. In a dream, Valentin begins hearing sounds from his environment (as does the audience), but cannot speak himself, then wakes up in a sweat. He decides to produce and direct his own silent film, financing it himself. The film opens on the same day as Peppy's new sound film, as well as the [[Wall Street Crash of 1929|1929 Stock Market Crash]]. Valentin's only chance of avoiding bankruptcy is for his film to be a hit. Unfortunately audiences flock to Peppy's film instead, and Valentin is ruined. His wife, Doris, kicks him out, and he moves into an apartment with his valet/chauffeur, Clifton, and his dog. Peppy goes on to become a major Hollywood star.\n\nLater, the bankrupt Valentin is forced to auction off all of his personal effects, and after realizing he has not paid loyal Clifton in over a year, gives him the car and fires him, telling him to get another job. Depressed and drunk, Valentin angrily sets a match to his private collection of his earlier films. As the [[Nitrocellulose#Film|nitrate film]] quickly blazes out of control he is overwhelmed by the smoke and passes out inside the burning house, still clutching a single film canister. However, Valentin's dog attracts the help of a nearby policeman, and after being rescued Valentin is hospitalized for injuries suffered in the fire. Peppy visits the hospital and discovers that the film he rescued is the one with them dancing together. She asks for him to be moved to her house to recuperate. Valentin awakens in a bed at her house, to find that Clifton is now working for Peppy. Valentin seems to remain dismissive of Peppy having taken him in, prompting Clifton to sternly remind Valentin of his changing luck.\n\nPeppy insists to Zimmer that Valentin co-star in her next film, threatening to quit Kinograph if Zimmer does not agree to her terms. After Valentin learns to his dismay that it had been Peppy who had purchased all his auctioned effects, he returns in despair to his burnt-out apartment. Peppy arrives, panicked, and finds that Valentin is about to attempt suicide with a handgun. Peppy tells him she only wanted to help him. They embrace and Valentin tells her it's no use; no one wants to hear him speak. Remembering Valentin's superb dancing ability, Peppy persuades Zimmer to let them make a [[Musical film#The classical sound era|musical]] together.\n\nNow the audience hears sound for the second time, as the film starts rolling for a dance scene with Peppy and Valentin and their tap-dancing can be heard. Once the choreography is complete, the two dancers are heard panting. The director of the musical calls out audibly, \"Cut!\" to which Zimmer adds: \"Perfect. Beautiful. Could you give me just one more?\" Valentin, in his only audible line, replies \"With pleasure,\" revealing a [[French accent]].<ref name=\"themarysue\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.themarysue.com/cinema-scope-a-short-history-of-the-end-of-silent-film/|title=Cinema Scope: A Short History of the End of Silent Film|accessdate=13 March 2013|publisher=[[Dan Abrams#The Mary Sue|The Mary Sue]]}}</ref> The camera then pulls back to the sounds of the film crew as they prepare to shoot another take.\n\n==Cast==\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n*[[Jean Dujardin]] as George Valentin\n*[[B\u00e9r\u00e9nice Bejo]] as Peppy Miller\n*[[Uggie]] as the dog, Jack\n*[[John Goodman]] as Al Zimmer\n*[[James Cromwell]] as Clifton\n*[[Missi Pyle]] as Constance\n*[[Penelope Ann Miller]] as Doris Valentin\n*[[Malcolm McDowell]] as The Butler\n*[[Bitsie Tulloch]] as Norma\n*[[Beth Grant]] as Peppy's maid\n*[[Ed Lauter]] as Peppy's first chauffeur\n*[[Jen Lilley]] as Onlooker\n*[[Nina Siemaszko]] as Admiring woman\n*[[Jewel Shepard]] as Flapper starlet\n*[[Basil Hoffman]] as Auctioneer\n*[[Ben Kurland]] as Casting assistant\n*[[Ken Davitian]] as Pawnbroker\n*[[Bill Fagerbakke]] as Policeman\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Production==\n[[File:\u00c9quipe The Artist Cannes 2011.jpg|thumb|400px|Some of the cast and crew at the [[2011 Cannes Film Festival]]: (left to right), score composer [[Ludovic Bource]], director [[Michel Hazanavicius]], stars [[Missi Pyle]], [[B\u00e9r\u00e9nice Bejo]], and [[Jean Dujardin]], director of photography [[Guillaume Schiffman]] and producer [[Thomas Langmann]].]]\nDirector [[Michel Hazanavicius]] had been fantasizing about making a [[silent film]] for many years, both because many filmmakers he admires emerged in the silent era, and because of the image-driven nature of the form. According to Hazanavicius, his wish to make a silent film was at first not taken seriously, but after the financial success of his spy-film pastiches ''[[OSS 117: Cairo, Nest of Spies]]'' and ''[[OSS 117: Lost in Rio]]'', producers started to express interest. The forming of the film's narrative started with Hazanavicius' desire to work again with actors [[Jean Dujardin]] and [[B\u00e9r\u00e9nice Bejo]], who had both starred in ''OSS 117: Cairo, Nest of Spies''. Hazanavicius chose the form of a [[melodrama]], mostly because he thought many of the films from the silent era that have aged best are of that genre. He did extensive research about 1920s Hollywood, and studied silent films to find the right techniques to make the story comprehensible without having to use too many [[intertitle]]s. The screenplay took four months to write and was principally inspired by the 1928 silent comedy, ''[[Show People]]''.<ref name=presskitmh>{{cite web|url=http://www.festival-cannes.com/assets/Image/Direct/041179.PDF |title=Interview with Michel Hazanavicius |work=English press kit The Artist |publisher=[[Wild Bunch (film company)|Wild Bunch]] |accessdate=10 May 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110914011421/http://www.festival-cannes.com/assets/Image/Direct/041179.PDF |archivedate=14 September 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nyu.edu/alumni.magazine/issue19/pdf/NYU19.pdf|title=The Clothes Make the Man|last=Alfuso|first=Renee|date=Fall 2012|work=NYU Alumni Magazine|access-date=24 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nChief among the influences shaping the screenplay's protagonist was [[Douglas Fairbanks]]. The Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences\u2019 recent book ''Douglas Fairbanks'', by [[Jeffrey Vance]], as well as the Academy's Douglas Fairbanks exhibition and screening events both in Los Angeles and New York City, afforded Hollywood's first swashbuckling hero and the Academy's first president some significant media attention.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.sfgate.com/tgladysz/2012/07/08/film-historian-jeffrey-vance-talks-about-douglas-fairbanks/|title=Film historian Jeffrey Vance talks about Douglas Fairbanks|author=Thomas Gladysz|date=8 July 2012|work=City Brights: Thomas Gladysz|accessdate=2 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://aaspeechesdb.oscars.org/link/084-1/|title=Academy Awards Acceptance Speeches - Search Results - Margaret Herrick Library - Academy of Motion Picture Arts & Sciences|publisher=|accessdate=2 April 2016}}</ref> \n\n[[Principal photography]] on ''The Artist'' began in November 2010,<ref>{{cite journal | author=Erin Carlson | url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/uggie-the-artist-retiring-287271 | title='The Artist' Dog Uggie Retiring Early Due to Mystery Illness (Report) | journal=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] | date=6 February 2014 | accessdate=1 September 2015}}</ref> taking place over the course of thirty-five days,<ref name=BAFTARed>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/iplayer/episode/b01c89nf/The_Orange_British_Academy_Film_Awards_2012_Red_Carpet/ |title=The Orange British Academy Film Awards&nbsp;\u2013 2012 Red Carpet |publisher=BBC News |accessdate=10 February 2012}}</ref> made in the 1.33:1 screen ratio commonly used in the silent film era. Though presented in black-and-white, it was shot in color by [[cinematographer]] [[Guillaume Schiffman]].<ref name=time>{{cite news|first=Gilbert|last=Cruz|title=What Is This Artist Movie That's Winning All the Awards? |url=http://entertainment.time.com/2012/01/19/what-is-this-artist-movie-thats-winning-all-the-awards/ |work=Time Magazine |date=19 January 2012 |accessdate=12 February 2012}}</ref> All the technical details, including lenses, lighting and camera moves, were calibrated to aesthetically match silent films of the period.<ref>Steve Rose, \"Now in full retrovision\", ''The Guardian'' (''The Guide'' supplement), 7 January 2012</ref> To recreate the slightly sped-up look of 1920s silent films, the film was shot at a slightly lower [[frame rate]] of 22 fps as opposed to the standard 24 fps.<ref>{{Cite news | author = Rebecca Keegan | title = Buzz is growing over a silent film | date = 21 November 2011 | url = http://articles.latimes.com/2011/nov/21/entertainment/la-ca-1120-artist-silent-movie-20111121 |work=Los Angeles Times | accessdate=28 January 2012}}</ref> Most of the film is silent, except for two brief scenes with sound as well as the [[Cinematic techniques#Sound|non-diegetic]] soundtrack. Throughout the shoot, Hazanavicius played music from classic Hollywood films while the actors performed.<ref name=presskitmh />\n\nThe film was produced by La Petite Reine and ARP S\u00e9lection for 13.47 million euro, including co-production support from Studio 37 and [[France 3|France 3 Cin\u00e9ma]], and pre-sales investment from [[Canal+]] and Cin\u00e9Cin\u00e9ma.<ref name=outofcomp>{{cite web|last=Lemercier|first=Fabien|date=18 April 2011|url=http://cineuropa.org/newsdetail.aspx?lang=en&documentID=201597|title=Media frenzy over Sarkozy's election ''Conquest''|work=Cineuropa|accessdate=10 May 2011}}</ref> The cast and the crew included both French and American members.<ref name=presskitmh /> All the scenes were shot in [[Los Angeles]], primarily in [[Hollywood]], but also in downtown theaters, restaurants and houses, including the one in which [[Mary Pickford]] lived. Soundstage work was done at [[Ren-Mar Studios|Red Studios]], and the studio lot itself doubled for part of the fictional Kinograph Studios lot, with Red's Lillian Way entrance doubling as the Kinograph entrance in several sequences. The iconic [[Bradbury Building]] in downtown L.A. provided the location for the film's distinctive staircase sequence. The dance sequence that closes the film took seventeen takes, and required Dujardin and Bejo to spend five months studying tap dancing, with Dujardin claiming that \"in the first week it's fun, the fifth week it's a little boring, at the end it's thrilling\".<ref>\"The Artist: The Making of An American Romance\" Featurette, ''The Artist'' DVD</ref>\n\nAmerican [[costume design]]er [[Mark Bridges (costume designer)|Mark Bridges]] created the wardrobe for the film's cast.<ref name=sfgate>{{cite news|first=Hugh|last=Hart|title='Artist' costumer had designs on career as child |url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2012/02/12/PKJC1N1Q6V.DTL |work=San Francisco Chronicle |date=12 February 2011 |accessdate=12 February 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Music==\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = The Artist: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack\n| type       = Soundtrack\n| artist     = [[Ludovic Bource]]\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = 10 October 2011\n| recorded   = 2011\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Soundtrack]]\n| length     = 77:39\n| label      = [[Sony Classical Records]]\n| producer   =\n| chronology = Ludovic Bource\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n{{Album ratings\n|rev1 = [http://www.filmtracks.com/titles/artist.html Filmtracks]\n|rev1score = {{rating|4|5}}\n|rev2 = [http://moviemusicuk.us/2011/11/29/the-artist-ludovic-bource/ Movie Music UK]\n|rev2score = {{rating|4|5}}\n|rev3 = [http://screeninvasion.com/2011/11/soundtrack-review-the-artist/#.UImCRW-HLng Screen Invasion]\n|rev3score = {{rating|5|5}}\n|rev4 = [http://staticmass.net/soundtracks/the-artist-soundtrack-cd-2012-review/ Static Mass Emporium]\n|rev4score = {{rating|5|5}}\n}}\nThe [[Film score|film's music]] was largely composed by [[Ludovic Bource]], but includes works by other composers such as [[Alberto Ginastera]]'s \"Estancia\". The soundtrack was recorded in Belgium by the [[Brussels Philharmonic]] and was conducted by Ernst Van Tiel; the Brussels Jazz Orchestra also cooperated. The recording took place during six days in April 2011 at [[Place Flagey|Flagey]]'s Studio 4 in Brussels.<ref>{{cite web|title=Soundtrack for 'The artist' recorded at Brussels|url=http://www.brusselsphilharmonic.be/en/news/detail/article/soundtrack-voor-the-artist-komt-uit-brussel/|publisher=Brussels Philharmonic|accessdate=30 January 2012|date=3 October 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe film's climactic scene is set to [[Bernard Herrmann]]'s \"Sc\u00e8ne d'amour\" from [[Vertigo (film score)|his score]] to [[Alfred Hitchcock]]'s film ''[[Vertigo (film)|Vertigo]]''. In ''Vertigo'', that composition similarly accompanies an extended scene without dialogue. Only one song (sung, with lyrics) is used in the soundtrack, \"[[Pennies from Heaven (song)|Pennies from Heaven]]\", sung by [[Rose Murphy|Rose \"Chi-Chi\" Murphy]] (uncredited). This song was written in 1936 although the film is set between 1927 and 1932.\n\nThe soundtrack was released on 21 October 2011 through [[Sony Classical Records]].<ref>{{cite web|title=The Artist|url=https://www.amazon.com/Artist-Ludovic-Bource/dp/B005LL4U54|publisher=Amazon.com|accessdate=30 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Track listing===\n{{Track listing\n| extra_column = Performer(s)\n| title1       = The Artist Ouverture\n| length1      = 1:02\n| extra1       = Ernst Van Tiel & the Brussels Philharmonic\n| title2       = 1927: A Russian Affair\n| length2      = 3:36\n| extra2       = Ernst Van Tiel & the Brussels Philharmonic\n| title3       = George Valentin\n| length3      = 5:35\n| extra3       = Ernst Van Tiel & the Brussels Philharmonic\n| title4       = Pretty Peppy\n| length4      = 2:32\n| extra4       = Ernst Van Tiel & the Brussels Philharmonic\n| title5       = At the Kinograph Studios\n| length5      = 1:37\n| extra5       = Ernst Van Tiel & the Brussels Philharmonic\n| title6       = Fantaisie d'amour\n| length6      = 3:09\n| extra6       = Ernst Van Tiel & the Brussels Philharmonic\n| title7       = Waltz for Peppy\n| length7      = 3:22\n| extra7       = Ernst Van Tiel & the Brussels Philharmonic\n| title8       = Estancia Op. 8 Movement 2\" <small>(written by Alberto Ginastera)</small>\n| length8      = 3:40\n| extra8       = Ernst Van Tiel & the Brussels Philharmonic\n| title9       = Imagination\n| length9      = 2:56\n| extra9       = [[Red Nichols]] & His Five Pennies\n| title10      = Silent Rumble\n| length10     = 1:16\n| extra10      = Ernst Van Tiel & the Brussels Philharmonic\n| title11      = 1929\n| length11     = 1:30\n| extra11      = Ernst Van Tiel & the Brussels Philharmonic\n| title12      = In the Stairs\n| length12     = 3:15\n| extra12      = Ernst Van Tiel & the Brussels Philharmonic\n| title13      = Jubilee Stomp\n| length13     = 2:33\n| extra13      = [[Duke Ellington]]\n| title14      = Comme une ros\u00e9e de larmes\n| length14     = 3:24\n| extra14      = Ernst Van Tiel & the Brussels Philharmonic\n| title15      = The Sound of Tears\n| length15     = 4:47\n| extra15      = Ernst Van Tiel & the Brussels Philharmonic\n| title16      = [[Pennies from Heaven (song)|Pennies from Heaven]]\n| length16     = 2:13\n| extra16      = [[Rose Murphy]]\n| title17      = 1931\n| length17     = 4:44\n| extra17      = Ernst Van Tiel & the Brussels Philharmonic\n| title18      = Jungle Bar\n| length18     = 2:07\n| extra18      = Ernst Van Tiel & the Brussels Philharmonic\n| title19      = L'Ombre des flammes\n| length19     = 5:57\n| extra19      = Ernst Van Tiel & the Brussels Philharmonic\n| title20      = Happy Ending...\n| length20     = 5:43\n| extra20      = Ernst Van Tiel & the Brussels Philharmonic\n| title21      = Charming Blackmail\n| length21     = 2:12\n| extra21      = Ernst Van Tiel & the Brussels Philharmonic\n| title22      = Ghosts from the Past\n| length22     = 2:00\n| extra22      = Ernst Van Tiel & the Brussels Philharmonic\n| title23      = My Suicide (Dedicated to 29 March 1967)\n| length23     = 6:24\n| extra23      = Ernst Van Tiel & the Brussels Philharmonic\n| title24      = Peppy and George\n| length24     = 2:05\n| extra24      = Ernst Van Tiel & the Brussels Philharmonic\n}}\n\n===Chart positions===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Chart (2012)\n!Peak<br>position\n|-\n{{albumchart|Flanders|52|artist=Soundtrack / Ludovic Bource|album=The Artist|accessdate=26 October 2013}}\n|-\n{{albumchart|Wallonia|70|artist=Soundtrack / Ludovic Bource|album=The Artist|accessdate=26 October 2013}}\n|-\n{{albumchart|France|37|artist=Soundtrack / Ludovic Bource|album=The Artist|accessdate=26 October 2013}}\n|-\n{{albumchart|Spain|37|artist=Soundtrack / Ludovic Bource|album=The Artist|accessdate=26 October 2013}}\n|-\n|US [[Top Soundtracks]] (''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'')<ref name = \"AllmusicAwards\">[http://www.allmusic.com/album/the-artist-mw0002246650/awards Ludovic Bource - The Artist Awards]. [[Allmusic]]. Retrieved 26 October 2013.</ref>\n|align=center|19\n|}\n\n===Certifications===\n{{Certification Table Top}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=France|type=album|artist=Ludovic Bource|title=The Artist|award=Platinum|relyear=2012|certyear=2012|certref=<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.actu.snepmusique.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/10/DISQUES-DOR-2012_site.pdf|title=ANNEE 2012 - CERTIFICATIONS AU 31/10/2012|publisher=[[Syndicat National de l'\u00c9dition Phonographique]]|year=2012|access-date=3 December 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121110045848/http://www.actu.snepmusique.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/10/DISQUES-DOR-2012_site.pdf|archivedate=10 November 2012}}</ref>}}\n{{Certification Table Bottom}}\n\n==Release==\n{{multiple image\n| align = right\n| image1 = Jean Dujardin Cannes 2011.jpg\n| width1 = 121\n| alt1 = \n| caption1 = \n| image2 = Berenice Bejo Cannes 2011 cropped.jpg\n| width2 = 110\n| alt2 = \n| caption2 = \n| footer = [[Jean Dujardin]] and [[B\u00e9r\u00e9nice Bejo]] at the [[2011 Cannes Film Festival]]\n}}\nThe film premiered on 15 May 2011 in competition at the [[2011 Cannes Film Festival]].<ref name=\"Cannes\">{{cite web|url=http://www.festival-cannes.fr/assets/File/Web/HORAIRES%202011/Horaire%20internet.pdf|title=Horaires 2011|language=French|work=festival-cannes.com|publisher=[[Cannes Film Festival]]|accessdate=10 May 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120123034309/http://www.festival-cannes.fr/assets/File/Web/HORAIRES%202011/Horaire%20internet.pdf|archive-date=23 January 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> It was initially announced as an out of competition entry, but was moved to the competition a week before the festival opened.<ref>{{cite web|last=Mitchell|first=Wendy|date=4 May 2011|url=http://www.screendaily.com/festivals/cannes/hazanavicius-the-artist-moves-into-competition-in-cannes/5026923.article|title=Hazanavicius' The Artist moves into Competition in Cannes|work=[[Screen International|Screen Daily]]|accessdate=10 May 2011}}</ref> The French regular release was on 12 October 2011 through [[Warner Bros.|Warner Bros. France]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allocine.fr/film/fichefilm_gen_cfilm=183070.html|title=The Artist|language=French|work=[[AlloCin\u00e9]]|publisher=[[Tiger Management|Tiger Global]]|accessdate=10 May 2011}}</ref> [[The Weinstein Company]] bought the distribution rights for the United States and Australia and [[Entertainment Film Distributors]] bought the UK distribution.<ref>{{cite web|last=Tartaglione|first=16 May 2011|url=http://www.screendaily.com/news/distribution/wild-bunch-weinsteins-confirm-multi-territory-deal-on-the-artist/5027596.article|title=Wild Bunch, Weinsteins confirm multi-territory deal on The Artist|work=[[Screen International|Screen Daily]]|accessdate=22 May 2011}}</ref> The film was initially given a [[limited release]] in the United States on 23 November 2011.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.cinemablend.com/new/Artist-Star-Jean-Dujardin-How-Gene-Kelly-Inspired-His-Work-28076.html | work=CinemaBlend.com | title=The Artist Star Jean Dujardin On How Gene Kelly Inspired His Work | date=28 November 2011 | accessdate=12 May 2012 | first1=Katey | last1=Rich}}</ref>\n\nFollowing its wins at the [[69th Golden Globe Awards]], it was announced Warner Bros. would re-release the film in France in 362 theaters on 25 January 2012.<ref>{{cite web|title=\" The Artist \" ressort en salles en France|url=http://archives.lesoir.be/-the-artist-ressort-en-salles-en-france_t-20120116-01RKP5.html|work=[[Le Soir]]|accessdate=27 February 2012|language=French|date=16 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Keslassy|first=Elsa|title=France's second look at 'Artist'|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1118050616|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|accessdate=27 February 2012|date=22 February 2012}}</ref> It was also re-released in Belgium on 22 February 2012.<ref>{{cite web|title=\"The Artist\" remporte 7 Bafta Awards dont meilleur film, meilleur r\u00e9alisateur et meillleur acteur.|url=http://www.cineart.be/fr/news/the-artist-remporte-7-bafta-awards-dont-meilleur-film-meilleur-realisateur-et-meilleur-acteur.aspx|publisher=cin\u00e9art.be|accessdate=27 February 2012|language=French|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130910140717/http://www.cineart.be/fr/news/the-artist-remporte-7-bafta-awards-dont-meilleur-film-meilleur-realisateur-et-meilleur-acteur.aspx|archivedate=10 September 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Box office===\n''The Artist'' grossed $44,671,682 in North America, along with $88,761,174 in other territories for a worldwide total of $133,432,856.<ref name=\"Boxofficemojo\" /> After its success at the Academy Awards, the film saw a moderate boost the following week on the box office in North America. It appeared on the week's top 10 chart and got an increase of 34% while expanding its release from 966 theaters to 1,756.<ref>{{cite news|last=McClintock|first=Pamela|title='The Artist' Enjoys Box Office Bump After Oscar Wins|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/artist-box-office-oscars-michel-Hazanavicius-Jean-Dujardin-296749|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media|Prometheus Global Media, LLC]]|accessdate=4 May 2012|date=4 March 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\n<!-- WHEN UPDATING REVIEW AGGREGATE SCORES, PLEASE MAKE SURE YOU UPDATE THE NUMBER OF REVIEWS AND THE ACCESS DATE IN THE CITATION! -->\nOn review aggregator [[Rotten Tomatoes]] the film has an approval rating of 95% based on 310 reviews, with an [[weighted arithmetic mean|average rating]] of 8.83/10. The website's critical consensus states, \"A crowd-pleasing tribute to the magic of silent cinema, ''The Artist'' is a clever, joyous film with delightful performances and visual style to spare.\"<ref name=\"RottenTomatoes\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/the_artist/|title=''The Artist'' (2011)|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango]]|accessdate=13 July 2019}}</ref> At [[Metacritic]], which assigns a weighted mean rating to reviews, the film received an average score of 89 out of 100, based on 41 critics, indicating \"universal acclaim\".<ref name=\"Metacritic\">{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/the-artist|title=''The Artist'' Reviews|work=[[Metacritic]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive|CBS Interactive Inc.]]|accessdate=27 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nMark Adams of ''[[Screen International|Screen Daily]]'' called the film \"a real pleasure\"; \"propelled elegantly forward by delightful performances from Jean Dujardin and B\u00e9r\u00e9nice Bejo it is the most unlikely of feel-good movies.\" He added however: \"The film does feel a little sluggish towards the end of the first third as the music is a little repetitive and the intertitles are infrequent, but Hazanavicius manages to give the film a real sense of charm and warmth, and film fans will be competing to spot visual and musical references.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Adams|first=Mark|date=15 May 2011|url=http://www.screendaily.com/reviews/latest-reviews/the-artist/5027562.article|title=The Artist|work=[[Screen International|Screen Daily]]|accessdate=22 May 2011}}</ref> Peter Bradshaw of ''[[The Guardian]]'' described how the film \"had me on my feet cheering throughout the final credits\" and stated \"I can't wait to see it again\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Bradshaw|first=Peter|authorlink=Peter Bradshaw|title=Cannes 2011: The Artist/Michael/Footnote&nbsp;\u2013 review|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2011/may/16/cannes-2011-the-artist-michael-footnote-review|work=[[The Guardian]]|publisher=[[Guardian Media Group|Guardian News and Media Limited]]|location=UK|accessdate=27 October 2011|date=16 May 2011}}</ref>\n\nGeoffrey McNab at ''[[The Independent]]'' called the film \"both a surefire crowdpleaser and a magnificent piece of film-making\" in his 5 star review from the [[Cannes Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite news|last=McNab|first=Geoffrey|title=The Artist, Cannes Film Festival|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/reviews/the-artist-cannes-film-festival-2285354.html|work=[[The Independent]]|publisher=Independent Digital News & Media Limited|location=UK|accessdate=27 October 2011|date=18 May 2011}}</ref> Rick Groen of ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'' assessed ''The Artist'' highly, noting the film \"uses old technology to dazzling effect to illustrate the insistent conquest of a new technology.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/arts/movies/the-artist-mostly-mute-it-speaks-volumes-about-silent-film/article2264777/|title=The Artist: Mostly mute, it speaks volumes about silent film|work=[[The Globe and Mail]]|publisher=The Globe and Mail Limited|first=Rick|last=Groen|date=9 December 2011|accessdate=13 January 2012|location=Toronto}}</ref> Sukanya Verma for [[Rediff.com]] feels ''The Artist'' is an extremely well-researched film and is an instant classic.<ref name=\"Review : The Artist \">{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/review/review-the-artist-is-an-instant-classic/20120224.htm| title=Review: The Artist is an instant classic | author=Sukanya Verma | publisher=Rediff.com | accessdate=24 February 2012}}</ref> David Thomson of ''[[The New Republic]]'' called ''The Artist'' an \"accomplished and witty entertainment\" and went on to write, \"Whether Hazanavicius can do more things as elegant and touching, without the gimmick of silence, remains to be seen (and heard). Meanwhile, he is to be congratulated on the grounds of pleasure alone. He may be due for much more in the way of rewards.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.tnr.com/article/film/99237/artist-cannes-hazanavicius-dujardin |title=Why \u2018The Artist\u2019 Just Might Win the Oscars |author=David Thomson | publisher=The New Republic | date= 5 January 2012}}</ref> ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' [[film criticism|film critic]] [[Roger Ebert]] gave the film four out of four stars, praising the performances, and calling the film \"one of the most entertaining films in many a moon, a film that charms because of its story, its performances and because of the sly way it plays with being silent and black and white.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Ebert|first=Roger|authorlink=Roger Ebert|url=http://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/the-artist-2011|title=The Artist review|website=[[RogerEbert.com]]|publisher=Ebert Digital LLC|date=25 July 2013}}</ref>\n\nWriting for ''[[Slant Magazine]]'', Jaime N. Christley gave the film one-and-a-half out of four stars, explaining Michel Hazanavicius ignores \"everything that's fascinating and memorable about the era, focusing instead on a patchwork of general knowledge, so eroded of inconvenient facts that it doesn't even qualify as a ''roman \u00e0 clef''.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Film Review \u2013 The Artist|url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/film/review/the-artist/5846|work=[[Slant Magazine]]|accessdate=27 February 2012|author=Jaime N. Christley|date=16 October 2011}}</ref> ''[[America (magazine)|America]]'' argued that while Jean Dujardin carried the film, Bejo's performance was disappointing.<ref name=\"america\">{{cite news |title=The French Connection |first=Victor |last=Stepien |url=http://www.americamagazine.org/content/culture.cfm?cultureID=258 |newspaper=[[America (Jesuit magazine)|America]] |date=12 March 2012 |accessdate=6 March 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Kim Novak controversy===\nOn 9 January 2012, actress [[Kim Novak]] stated that \"rape\" had been committed in the film's licensed use of a portion of [[Bernard Herrmann]]'s score from [[Alfred Hitchcock]]'s 1958 film ''[[Vertigo (film)|Vertigo]]'' (in which Novak starred). The final portion of ''The Artist'' is accompanied not by original music, but by a 1992 recording of the Herrmann composition ''Scene d'Amour'', conducted by [[Elmer Bernstein]]. In the article published, by ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'', she stated that \"I feel as if my body&nbsp;\u2014 or at least my body of work&nbsp;\u2014 has been violated by the movie.\"<ref name=\"Vertigo\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-16482624|title=Artist director responds to Kim Novak Vertigo claim|work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |accessdate=10 January 2012 |date=10 January 2012}}</ref> \"This film should've been able to stand on its own without depending on Bernard Herrmann's score from Alfred Hitchcock's 'Vertigo' to provide more drama\" and that \"It is morally wrong for the artistry of our industry to use and abuse famous pieces of work to gain attention and applause for other than what they were intended\", ending her comments with \"Shame on them!\"<ref name=\"CNN\">{{cite news|title='The Artist' director defends use of Hitchcock score|url=http://marquee.blogs.cnn.com/2012/01/10/the-artist-director-defends-use-of-hitchcock-score/|work=The Marquee Blog|publisher=CNN|accessdate=12 January 2012|date=10 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn response, director Hazanavicius released a statement:<blockquote>''The Artist'' was made as a love letter to cinema, and grew out of my (and all of my cast and crew\u2019s) admiration and respect for movies throughout history. It was inspired by the work of Hitchcock, [[Fritz Lang|Lang]], [[John Ford|Ford]], [[Ernst Lubitsch|Lubitsch]], [[F. W. Murnau|Murnau]] and [[Billy Wilder|Wilder]]. I love Bernard Herrmann and his music has been used in many different films and I\u2019m very pleased to have it in mine. I respect Kim Novak greatly and I\u2019m sorry to hear she disagrees.<ref>{{cite news|title='The Artist' Director Responds to Kim Novak Slam Over 'Vertigo' Music|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/race/artist-kim-novak-michel-hazanavicius-279757|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=12 January 2012|date=9 January 2012}}</ref></blockquote> Hazanavicius also told [[CNN]] \"I used music from another movie, but it\u2019s not illegal. We paid for that, we asked for that and we had the permission to do it. For me there is no real controversy.... I feel sorry for her, but there\u2019s a lot of movies with music from other movies, directors do that all the time and I\u2019m not sure it\u2019s a big deal.\"<ref name=\"CNN\" />\n\nIn May 2011, when the film was first shown at the Cannes Festival, [[Todd McCarthy]] from ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' mentioned the use of Herrmann's music, \"Hazanavicius and Bource daringly choose to explicitly employ Bernard Herrmann\u2019s love theme from ''Vertigo'', which is dramatically effective in its own right but is so well known that it yanks you out of one film and places you in the mind-set of another. Surely some sort of reworked equivalent would have been a better idea.\"<ref name=McCarthy>{{cite news|last=McCarthy|first=Todd|title=The Artist: Cannes Review|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/artist-cannes-review-188493|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media|Prometheus Global Media, LLC]]|accessdate=12 January 2012|date=15 May 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Top ten lists===\nThe film has appeared on the following critics' top ten lists for the best films of 2011:\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 100%;\"\n|-\n! Critic\n! Publication\n! Rank\n|- 1st.\n| [[Richard Corliss]] || ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]''||1st<ref>{{cite news|last=Corliss|first=Richard|title=The Top 10 Everything of 2011&nbsp;\u2013 The Artist|url=http://www.time.com/time/specials/packages/article/0,28804,2101344_2101362_2101351,00.html|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|accessdate=17 December 2011|date=7 December 2011}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Peter Bradshaw]] || ''[[The Guardian]]''||1st<ref name=\"metacritic top ten\">{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/feature/movie-critic-best-of-2011-top-ten-lists |title=2011 Film Critic Top Ten Lists [Updated Dec. 22] |first=Jason |last=Dietz |work=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |date=8 December 2011 |accessdate=23 December 2011}}</ref>\n|-\n| Robbie Collin || ''[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]''||1st<ref name=\"metacritic top ten\" />\n|-\n| [[Richard Roeper]] || ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''||2nd<ref>{{cite web |url=http://awardcontenders.com/top-10-lists-from-richard-roeper-michael-phillips-j-hoberman-and-todd-mccarthy/ |title=Top 10 Lists from Richard Roeper, Michael Phillips, J. Hoberman, and Todd McCarthy |work=Chicago Tribune |date=22 December 2011 |accessdate=19 April 2011}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Peter Travers]] || ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' ||2nd<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/lists/10-best-movies-of-2011-20111207/the-artist-19691231|title=10 Best Movies of 2011: The Artist |first=Peter |last=Travers |work=Rolling Stone|date=8 December 2011 |accessdate=17 December 2011}}</ref>\n|-\n| Elizabeth Weitzman||''[[New York Daily News]]''||2nd<ref name=\"metacritic top ten\"/>\n|-\n| [[Lisa Schwarzbaum]] || ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' || 3rd<ref name=\"metacritic top ten\"/>\n|-\n| [[Mark Kermode]] || [[BBC Radio 5 Live]] || 4th<ref>{{cite web|title=\nEleven from Eleven |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/markkermode/2012/01/eleven_from_eleven.html |work=BBC |accessdate=11 January 2012|date=6 January 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n| Richard T. Jameson || [[MSN|MSN Movies]] || 4th<ref name=\"metacritic top ten\"/>\n|-\n| Sean Axmaker || MSN Movies || 5th<ref name=\"metacritic top ten\"/>\n|-\n| ''Empire''{{'}}s writers and contributors || ''[[Empire Magazine]]''||5th<ref name=\"metacritic top ten\" />\n|-\n| [[James Berardinelli]] || ''Reelviews'' || 5th<ref>{{cite web|title=Rewinding 2011: The Top 10 |url=http://www.reelviews.net/reelthoughts.php?identifier=683 |work=Reelviews |accessdate=26 February 2012|date=31 December 2011}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''S&S'' international poll of critics || ''[[Sight & Sound]]'' ||5th<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bfi.org.uk/sightandsound/feature/49804|title=2011: The year in review|work=Sight & Sound|date=17 December 2011|accessdate=17 December 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120104140414/http://www.bfi.org.uk/sightandsound/feature/49804|archivedate=4 January 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n| Austin Film Critics Association || [[Austin Film Critics Association]] ||6th<ref>{{cite web|url=http://austinfilmcritics.org/2011.html|title=2011 Awards|work=Austin Film Critics|date=17 December 2011|accessdate=17 December 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120108081300/http://austinfilmcritics.org/2011.html|archivedate=8 January 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Roger Ebert]] || ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' || 10th<ref name=\"metacritic top ten\"/>\n|-\n| ''Time Out''{{'}}s film team || ''[[Time Out London]]'' || 10th<ref name=\"metacritic top ten\"/>\n|}\n\n===Accolades===\n{{main|List of accolades received by The Artist (film)}}\nAt the [[65th British Academy Film Awards]], the film won seven awards, including Best Film, Best Actor for Dujardin, Best Original Screenplay for Hazanavicius, Cinematography for Schiffman, Costume Design for Bridges and Original Score for [[Ludovic Bource]].<ref name=\"Orange BAFTA Film Award Winners\">{{cite web |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/movies/news/a364820/orange-bafta-film-awards-2012-winners-list-in-full.html |title=Orange BAFTA Film Awards 2012 winners list&nbsp;\u2014 in full |publisher=Digital Bits |accessdate=16 February 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"BAFTA 2012 Winners\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2012/feb/12/baftas-2012-winners-full-list?intcmp=239 |title=BAFTA 2012 the winners&nbsp;\u2014 the full list |work=The Guardian |location=UK |date=12 February 2012 |accessdate=16 February 2012}}</ref> At the [[69th Golden Globe Awards]], the film was nominated for six [[Golden Globes]] to win three of them; [[Golden Globe Award for Best Motion Picture - Musical or Comedy|Best Motion Picture&nbsp;\u2013 Musical or Comedy]], [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor - Motion Picture Musical or Comedy|Best Actor&nbsp;\u2013 Motion Picture Musical or Comedy]] for Dujardin and [[Golden Globe Award for Best Musical Score|Best Musical Score]] for Bource.<ref name=\"Golden Globes 2012 Winners\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2012/jan/16/golden-globes-golden-globes-2012 |title=Golden Globes 2012 the winners&nbsp;\u2014 the full list |work=The Guardian |location=UK |date=16 January 2012 |accessdate=17 February 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Golden Globes 2012\">{{cite news |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/golden-globes-2012-winners-list-282032 |title=Golden Globes 2012: The Full List |work=The Hollywood Reporter |date=15 January 2012 |accessdate=17 February 2012}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[84th Academy Awards]], ''The Artist'' received ten nominations, winning five awards, including [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]], [[Academy Award for Best Director|Best Director]] for Hazanavicius, [[Academy Award for Best Actor|Best Actor in a Leading Role]] for [[Jean Dujardin]], [[Academy Award for Best Costume Design|Best Costume Design]], and [[Academy Award for Best Original Score|Best Original Score]].<ref name=\"Oscar winners 2012\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2012/feb/27/oscars-2012-full-list-winners |title=Oscar 2012 winners&nbsp;\u2013 The full list |work=The Guardian |location=UK |date=27 February 2012 |accessdate=28 February 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Academy Awards 2012 winners\">{{cite web |url=http://www.oscars.org/awards/academyawards/84/nominees.html |title=Nominees and Winners for the 84th Academy Awards |publisher=Academy Awards of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences (Oscars) |accessdate=21 February 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-17178811\n|title=France hails The Artist's Oscars triumph |date=27 February 2012 |work=BBC News |accessdate=27 February 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Home media===\n''The Artist'' was released on [[DVD region code|region 1]] [[DVD]] and [[Blu-ray Disc|Blu-ray]] on 26 June 2012.<ref name=Amazon>{{cite web|title=Amazon.com|url=https://www.amazon.com/The-Artist-UltraViolet-Digital-Copy/dp/B00782O7IY/ref=sr_1_1?ie=UTF8&qid=1337129571&sr=8-1|work=Amazon|date=15 May 2012}}</ref> It was released in the UK by [[Entertainment Film Distributors|Entertainment in Video]] on 28 May 2012.<ref>{{cite web|author1=Webmaster|title=The Artist Detailed|url=http://www.blu-ray.com/news/?id=8486|website=Blu-ray.com|publisher=Blu-ray.com|accessdate=12 November 2017|date=4 April 2012}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of black-and-white films produced since 1970]]\n*[[List of films featuring fictional films]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|1|group=nb}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|The Artist (film)}}\n*[http://www.orange-studio.fr/film/264/the-artist.html Orange Studio (Studio 37) official site] {{in lang|fr}}\n*{{IMDb title|1655442}}\n*{{Allmovie title|538544}}\n*{{Mojo title|artist}}\n*{{Metacritic film|the-artist}}\n*{{Rotten Tomatoes|the_artist}}\n\n{{Michel Hazanavicius}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title = [[List of accolades received by The Artist (film)|Awards for ''The Artist'']]\n|list =\n{{AcademyAwardBestPicture 2001\u20132020}}\n{{AACTA International Award for Best Film}}\n{{BAFTA Best Film 2001\u20132020}}\n{{Broadcast Film Critics Association Award for Best Film}}\n{{C\u00e9sar Award for Best Film}}\n{{GoldenGlobeBestMotionPictureMusicalComedy 2001\u20132020}}\n{{Goya Award for Best European Film}}\n{{Independent Spirit Award for Best Film}}\n{{London Film Critics Circle Award for Film of the Year}}\n{{Lumi\u00e8res Award for Best Film}}\n{{New York Film Critics Circle Award for Best Film}}\n{{Producers Guild of America Award for Best Theatrical Motion Picture}}\n{{Vancouver Film Critics Circle Award for Best Film}}\n}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Artist}}\n[[Category:2011 films]]\n[[Category:French films]]\n[[Category:2010s romantic comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:French comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:French romantic comedy films]]\n[[Category:French romantic drama films]]\n[[Category:French silent feature films]]\n[[Category:French black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Michel Hazanavicius]]\n[[Category:Films about actors]]\n[[Category:Films about Hollywood]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1927]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1928]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1929]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1930]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1931]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1932]]\n[[Category:Films set in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Best Picture Academy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Best Film BAFTA Award winners]]\n[[Category:Best Film Lumi\u00e8res Award winners]]\n[[Category:Best Film C\u00e9sar Award winners]]\n[[Category:Best Musical or Comedy Picture Golden Globe winners]