{"title_page": "Lo-Toga language", "text_new": "{{Infobox language\n|name=Lo-Toga\n|altname=Loh, Toga\n|dialects=Lo, Toga\n|states=[[Vanuatu]]\n|region=[[Torres Islands]]\n|speakers=580\n|date=2012\n|ref=<ref>[[#AF-diversity|Fran\u00e7ois (2012)]]:88).</ref>\n|familycolor=Austronesian\n|fam2=[[Malayo-Polynesian languages|Malayo-Polynesian]]\n|fam3=[[Oceanic languages|Oceanic]]\n|fam4=[[Southern Oceanic languages|Southern Oceanic]]\n|fam5=Vanuatu\n|fam6=[[North Vanuatu languages|North Vanuatu]]\n|fam7=[[Torres\u2013Banks languages|Torres\u2013Banks]]\n|iso3=lht\n|glotto=loto1240\n|glottorefname=Lo-Toga\n}}\n\n'''Lo-Toga''' is an [[Oceanic language]] spoken by about 580 people on the islands of [[Lo island|Lo]] and [[Toga island|Toga]], in the [[Torres Islands|Torres group]] of northern [[Vanuatu]].<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Fran\u00e7ois|2005|p=444}}</ref> The language has sometimes been called ''Loh'' <small>(''[[sic]]'')</small> or ''Toga'', after either of its two dialects.\n\n==Situation and dialects==\nIts 580 speakers live mostly in [[Lo (island)|Lo]] and [[Toga Island|Toga]], the two main islands in the southern half of the Torres group. The same language is also spoken by the small populations of the two other islands of [[Linua]] and [[Tegua]].\n\nLo-Toga is itself divided into two very close dialects, ''Lo'' (spoken on Lo island) and ''Toga'' (spoken on Toga). \n\nConversely, Lo-Toga is a distinct language from the other language of the Torres group, [[Hiw language|Hiw]].\n\n==Phonology==\nThe Lo dialect of Lo-Toga has 13 [[phoneme|phonemic]] vowels. These include 8 [[monophthong]]s /i e \u025b a \u0259 \u0254 o \u0289/, and five [[diphthong]]s /i\u0361e i\u0361\u025b i\u0361a o\u0361\u0259 o\u0361\u0254/.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Fran\u00e7ois|2005|p=460}}; {{Harvcoltxt|Fran\u00e7ois|2011|p=194}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|+ Lo-Toga vowels\n! rowspan=\"2\" |\n! colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Monophthong|Monophthongs]]\n! rowspan=\"7\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| \n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Diphthong|Diphthongs]]\n|-\n! |<small>[[Front vowel|Front]]</small>\n! |<small>[[Central vowel|Central]]</small>\n! |<small>[[Back vowel|Back]]</small>\n! |<small>[[Front vowel|Front]]</small>\n! |<small>[[Back vowel|Back]]</small>\n|-\n! [[Close vowel|Close]]\n| {{IPA link|i}}  || {{IPA link|\u0289}} || || colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| \n|-\n! [[close-mid vowel|Close-mid]]\n| {{IPA link|e}} ||  || {{IPA link|o}} || {{IPA|i\u0361e}} || \n|-\n! [[mid vowel|Mid]]\n|colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{IPA link|\u0259}} ||  || {{IPA|o\u0361\u0259}}\n|-\n! [[open-mid vowel|Open-mid]]\n| {{IPA link|\u025b}} ||  || {{IPA link|\u0254}} || {{IPA|i\u0361\u025b}} || {{IPA|o\u0361\u0254}}\n|-\n! [[open vowel|Open]]\n| colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{IPA link|a}} || colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{IPA|i\u200b\u0361a}}\n|}\n\n==Grammar==\nLo-Toga presents various forms of [[verb serialization]].<ref>[[#demotion|Fran\u00e7ois (2010:]] 511-512).</ref>\n\nThe system of [[personal pronoun]]s contrasts [[clusivity]], and distinguishes three [[Grammatical number|numbers]] (singular, [[Dual number|dual]], plural).<ref>[[#pronouns|Fran\u00e7ois (2016)]].</ref>\n\nTogether with its neighbour [[Hiw language|Hiw]], Lo-Toga has developed a rich system of [[verbal number]], whereby certain verbs change their root depending on the number of their main participant.<ref name=\"number\">[[#number|Fran\u00e7ois (2019)]].</ref> Lo-Toga has 18 such pairs of verbs.\n\nSpatial reference in Lo-Toga is based on a system of geocentric ([[Linguistic frame of reference#Absolute frame of reference|absolute]]) directionals, which is in part typical of [[Oceanic languages]], and yet innovative.<ref>[[#updown|Fran\u00e7ois (2015:]] 175-176).</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2|}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{citation\n|doi=10.1353/ol.2005.0034\n|last=Fran\u00e7ois\n|first=Alexandre\n|author-link = Alexandre Fran\u00e7ois (linguist)\n|year=2005\n|title=Unraveling the history of vowels in seventeen north Vanuatu languages\n|journal=Oceanic Linguistics\n|volume=44\n|issue=2\n|pages=443\u2013504\n|url=http://alex.francois.online.fr/data/AlexFrancois_VowelsNorthernVanuatu_OL44-2.pdf\n|citeseerx=10.1.1.395.4359\n}}\n*{{Citation\n  | last = Fran\u00e7ois\n  | first = Alexandre\n  | author-link = \n  | contribution = Pragmatic demotion and clause dependency: On two atypical subordinating strategies in Lo-Toga and Hiw (Torres, Vanuatu)\n  | editor-last = Bril\n  | editor-first = Isabelle\n  | title = Clause hierarchy and Clause linking: The Syntax and Pragmatics interface\n  | volume = \n  | pages = 499\u2013548\n  | publisher = Benjamins\n  | place = Amsterdam\n  | year = 2010\n  | contribution-url = http://alex.francois.online.fr/data/AlexFrancois_2010_Pragmatic-demotion-Subordination-Torres.pdf\n  | ref = demotion\n }}\n* {{citation\n|last=Fran\u00e7ois\n|first=Alexandre\n|year=2011\n|title=Social ecology and language history in the northern Vanuatu linkage: A tale of divergence and convergence\n|journal=Journal of Historical Linguistics\n|volume=1\n|issue=2\n|pages=175\u2013246\n|doi=10.1075/jhl.1.2.03fra\n|url=http://alex.francois.online.fr/data/AlexFrancois_2011_JHL1-2_Social-ecology_Vanuatu.pdf\n}}\n*{{citation\n|last=Fran\u00e7ois\n|first=Alexandre\n|year=2012\n|title=The dynamics of linguistic diversity: Egalitarian multilingualism and power imbalance among northern Vanuatu languages\n|journal=International Journal of the Sociology of Language\n|volume=2012\n|issue=214\n|doi=10.1515/ijsl-2012-0022\n|pages=85\u2013110\n|url=http://alex.francois.online.fr/data/AlexFrancois_2012_NorthVanuatuSocioling_IJSL.pdf\n|ref=AF-diversity\n}}\n* {{Cite book\n | publisher = Asia-Pacific Linguistics\n | isbn = 978-1-922185-23-5\n | pages = 137\u2013195\n | editors = Alexandre Fran\u00e7ois, S\u00e9bastien Lacrampe, Michael Franjieh, Stefan Schnell (eds.)\n | last = Fran\u00e7ois\n | first = Alexandre\n | title = The languages of Vanuatu: Unity and diversity\n | chapter = The ins and outs of ''up'' and ''down'': Disentangling the nine geocentric space systems of Torres and Banks languages\n | location = Canberra\n | series = Studies in the Languages of Island Melanesia\n | url = http://hdl.handle.net/1885/14819\n | contribution-url= http://alex.francois.online.fr/data/AlexFrancois_2015_North-Vanuatu-space-directionals.pdf\n | date = 2015\n | ref = updown }}\n*{{citation\n|last=Fran\u00e7ois\n|first=Alexandre\n|year=2016\n|contribution = The historical morphology of personal pronouns in northern Vanuatu\n|editor1-last = Pozdniakov\n|editor1-first = Konstantin\n|title = Comparatisme et reconstruction : tendances actuelles\n|volume = 47\n|pages = 25\u201360\n|publisher = Peter Lang\n|place = Bern\n|series = ''Faits de Langues''\n|contribution-url= http://alex.francois.online.fr/data/AlexFrancois_2016_History-personal-pronouns_north-Vanuatu_s.pdf\n|ref=pronouns\n}}\n* {{Cite journal\n| doi = 10.1111/1467-968X.12168\n| issn = \n| volume = 117\n| issue = 3\n| pages = 338\u2013371\n| last = Fran\u00e7ois\n| first = Alexandre\n| title = Verbal number in Lo\u2013Toga and Hiw: The emergence of a lexical paradigm\n| journal = Transactions of the Philological Society\n| year = 2019\n| url = http://alex.francois.online.fr/data/AlexFrancois_2019_Verbal-number-in-Hiw-and-LoToga_TPhS.pdf\n| ref= number }}.\n\n==External links==\n* [http://alex.francois.online.fr/AlexFrancois_Torba-languages_map.htm Linguistic map of north Vanuatu, showing range of Lo-Toga].\n* [https://pangloss.cnrs.fr/corpus/list_rsc_en.php?lg=Lo-Toga Audio recordings in the Lo-Toga language], in open access, by [[Alexandre Fran\u00e7ois|A. Fran\u00e7ois]] <small>(source: ''[[Pangloss Collection]]'')</small>.\n* [http://alex.francois.online.fr/AF-dict-Lo-Toga_e.htm Online Lo-Toga\u2014English dictionary] <small>(work in progress)</small>\n* [http://mammana.org/bcp/toga/ Ne Vavatema Vivda Pah Tage Vivda Volquane Lema Rua] Portions of the Book of Common Prayer in Toga (1907)\n\n{{Languages of Vanuatu}}\n{{Southern Oceanic languages}}\n\n[[Category:Languages of Vanuatu]]\n[[Category:Banks\u2013Torres languages]]\n[[Category:Torba Province]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox language\n|name=Lo-Toga\n|altname=Loh, Toga\n|dialects=Lo, Toga\n|states=[[Vanuatu]]\n|region=[[Torres Islands]]\n|speakers=580\n|date=2012\n|ref=<ref>[[#AF-diversity|Fran\u00e7ois (2012)]]:88).</ref>\n|familycolor=Austronesian\n|fam2=[[Malayo-Polynesian languages|Malayo-Polynesian]]\n|fam3=[[Oceanic languages|Oceanic]]\n|fam4=[[Southern Oceanic languages|Southern Oceanic]]\n|fam5=Vanuatu\n|fam6=[[North Vanuatu languages|North Vanuatu]]\n|fam7=[[Torres\u2013Banks languages|Torres\u2013Banks]]\n|iso3=lht\n|glotto=loto1240\n|glottorefname=Lo-Toga\n}}\n\n'''Lo-Toga''' is an [[Oceanic language]] spoken by about 580 people on the islands of [[Lo island|Lo]] and [[Toga island|Toga]], in the [[Torres Islands|Torres group]] of northern [[Vanuatu]].<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Fran\u00e7ois|2005|p=444}}</ref> The language has sometimes been called ''Loh'' <small>(''[[sic]]'')</small> or ''Toga'', after either of its two dialects.\n\n==Situation and dialects==\nIts 580 speakers live mostly in [[Lo (island)|Lo]] and [[Toga Island|Toga]], the two main islands in the southern half of the Torres group. The same language is also spoken by the small populations of the two other islands of [[Linua]] and [[Tegua]].\n\nLo-Toga is itself divided into two very close dialects, ''Lo'' (spoken on Lo island) and ''Toga'' (spoken on Toga). \n\nConversely, Lo-Toga is a distinct language from the other language of the Torres group, [[Hiw language|Hiw]].\n\n==Phonology==\nThe Lo dialect of Lo-Toga has 13 [[phoneme|phonemic]] vowels. These include 8 [[monophthong]]s /i e \u025b a \u0259 \u0254 o \u0289/, and five [[diphthong]]s /i\u0361e i\u0361\u025b i\u0361a o\u0361\u0259 o\u0361\u0254/.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Fran\u00e7ois|2005|p=460}}; {{Harvcoltxt|Fran\u00e7ois|2011|p=194}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|+ Lo-Toga vowels\n! rowspan=\"2\" |\n! colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Monophthong|Monophthongs]]\n! rowspan=\"7\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| \n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Diphthong|Diphthongs]]\n|-\n! |<small>[[Front vowel|Front]]</small>\n! |<small>[[Central vowel|Central]]</small>\n! |<small>[[Back vowel|Back]]</small>\n! |<small>[[Front vowel|Front]]</small>\n! |<small>[[Back vowel|Back]]</small>\n|-\n! [[Close vowel|Close]]\n| {{IPA link|i}}  || {{IPA link|\u0289}} || || colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| \n|-\n! [[close-mid vowel|Close-mid]]\n| {{IPA link|e}} ||  || {{IPA link|o}} || {{IPA|i\u0361e}} || \n|-\n! [[mid vowel|Mid]]\n|colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{IPA link|\u0259}} ||  || {{IPA|o\u0361\u0259}}\n|-\n! [[open-mid vowel|Open-mid]]\n| {{IPA link|\u025b}} ||  || {{IPA link|\u0254}} || {{IPA|i\u0361\u025b}} || {{IPA|o\u0361\u0254}}\n|-\n! [[open vowel|Open]]\n| colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{IPA link|a}} || colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{IPA|i\u200b\u0361a}}\n|}\n\n==Grammar==\nLo-Toga presents various forms of [[verb serialization]].<ref>[[#demotion|Fran\u00e7ois (2010:]] 511-512).</ref>\n\nThe system of [[personal pronoun]]s contrasts [[clusivity]], and distinguishes three [[Grammatical number|numbers]] (singular, [[Dual number|dual]], plural).<ref>[[#pronouns|Fran\u00e7ois (2016)]].</ref>\n\nTogether with its neighbour [[Hiw language|Hiw]], Lo-Toga has developed a rich system of [[verbal number]], whereby certain verbs change their root depending on the number of their main participant.<ref name=\"number\">[[#number|Fran\u00e7ois (2019)]].</ref> Lo-Toga has 18 such pairs of verbs.\n\nSpatial reference in Lo-Toga is based on a system of geocentric ([[Linguistic frame of reference#Absolute frame of reference|absolute]]) directionals, which is in part typical of [[Oceanic languages]], and yet innovative.<ref>[[#updown|Fran\u00e7ois (2015:]] 175-176).</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2|}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{citation\n|doi=10.1353/ol.2005.0034\n|last=Fran\u00e7ois\n|first=Alexandre\n|author-link = Alexandre Fran\u00e7ois (linguist)\n|year=2005\n|title=Unraveling the history of vowels in seventeen north Vanuatu languages\n|journal=Oceanic Linguistics\n|volume=44\n|issue=2\n|pages=443\u2013504\n|url=http://alex.francois.online.fr/data/AlexFrancois_VowelsNorthernVanuatu_OL44-2.pdf\n|citeseerx=10.1.1.395.4359\n}}\n*{{Citation\n  | last = Fran\u00e7ois\n  | first = Alexandre\n  | author-link = \n  | contribution = Pragmatic demotion and clause dependency: On two atypical subordinating strategies in Lo-Toga and Hiw (Torres, Vanuatu)\n  | editor-last = Bril\n  | editor-first = Isabelle\n  | title = Clause hierarchy and Clause linking: The Syntax and Pragmatics interface\n  | volume = \n  | pages = 499\u2013548\n  | publisher = Benjamins\n  | place = Amsterdam\n  | year = 2010\n  | contribution-url = http://alex.francois.online.fr/data/AlexFrancois_2010_Pragmatic-demotion-Subordination-Torres.pdf\n  | ref = demotion\n }}\n* {{citation\n|last=Fran\u00e7ois\n|first=Alexandre\n|year=2011\n|title=Social ecology and language history in the northern Vanuatu linkage: A tale of divergence and convergence\n|journal=Journal of Historical Linguistics\n|volume=1\n|issue=2\n|pages=175\u2013246\n|doi=10.1075/jhl.1.2.03fra\n|url=http://alex.francois.online.fr/data/AlexFrancois_2011_JHL1-2_Social-ecology_Vanuatu.pdf\n}}\n*{{citation\n|last=Fran\u00e7ois\n|first=Alexandre\n|year=2012\n|title=The dynamics of linguistic diversity: Egalitarian multilingualism and power imbalance among northern Vanuatu languages\n|journal=International Journal of the Sociology of Language\n|volume=2012\n|issue=214\n|doi=10.1515/ijsl-2012-0022\n|pages=85\u2013110\n|url=http://alex.francois.online.fr/data/AlexFrancois_2012_NorthVanuatuSocioling_IJSL.pdf\n|ref=AF-diversity\n}}\n* {{Cite book\n | publisher = Asia-Pacific Linguistics\n | isbn = 978-1-922185-23-5\n | pages = 137\u2013195\n | editors = Alexandre Fran\u00e7ois, S\u00e9bastien Lacrampe, Michael Franjieh, Stefan Schnell (eds.)\n | last = Fran\u00e7ois\n | first = Alexandre\n | title = The languages of Vanuatu: Unity and diversity\n | chapter = The ins and outs of ''up'' and ''down'': Disentangling the nine geocentric space systems of Torres and Banks languages\n | location = Canberra\n | series = Studies in the Languages of Island Melanesia\n | url = http://alex.francois.online.fr/data/AlexFrancois_2015_North-Vanuatu-space-directionals.pdf\n | date = 2015\n | ref = updown }}\n*{{citation\n|last=Fran\u00e7ois\n|first=Alexandre\n|year=2016\n|contribution = The historical morphology of personal pronouns in northern Vanuatu\n|editor1-last = Pozdniakov\n|editor1-first = Konstantin\n|title = Comparatisme et reconstruction : tendances actuelles\n|volume = 47\n|pages = 25\u201360\n|publisher = Peter Lang\n|place = Bern\n|series = ''Faits de Langues''\n|contribution-url= http://alex.francois.online.fr/data/AlexFrancois_2016_History-personal-pronouns_north-Vanuatu_s.pdf\n|ref=pronouns\n}}\n* {{Cite journal\n| doi = 10.1111/1467-968X.12168\n| issn = \n| volume = 117\n| issue = 3\n| pages = 338\u2013371\n| last = Fran\u00e7ois\n| first = Alexandre\n| title = Verbal number in Lo\u2013Toga and Hiw: The emergence of a lexical paradigm\n| journal = Transactions of the Philological Society\n| year = 2019\n| url = http://alex.francois.online.fr/data/AlexFrancois_2019_Verbal-number-in-Hiw-and-LoToga_TPhS.pdf\n| ref= number }}.\n\n==External links==\n* [http://alex.francois.online.fr/AlexFrancois_Torba-languages_map.htm Linguistic map of north Vanuatu, showing range of Lo-Toga].\n* [https://pangloss.cnrs.fr/corpus/list_rsc_en.php?lg=Lo-Toga Audio recordings in the Lo-Toga language], in open access, by [[Alexandre Fran\u00e7ois|A. Fran\u00e7ois]] <sm